October 9, 2023 (Monday) The crisis in the Middle East has continued to escalate. Since I last wrote on Saturday, October 7, the contours of the attack on Israel by Hamas have become clearer. More than 900 Israelis have been killed in the fighting, and dozens more have been taken hostage and are now being held in Gaza, with Hamas threatening to execute them if Israelis target civilians without warning. At least 11 U.S. citizens were killed in the attack. In retaliation, Israel has struck the Gaza Strip from the air and restricted food, electricity, and fuel. Around 680 people have been killed in Gaza, and more than 187,500 have been displaced. Thousands more have been wounded on both sides. Rumors are flying about how deeply Iran backed the attack by Hamas, and whether Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu knew ahead of time about the attack, but there is little analysis yet that is verified. At the same time, the volume of disinformation spreading suggests that the crisis is being used to destabilize the U.S. by increasing the already strong feelings about the conflicts between Israelis and Arabs in the Middle East. And, over all, the conflict is deeply steeped in centuries of history both in the region and elsewhere as well as in longstanding cultural antisemitism, which had been on the rise and which is now, in some countries, at fever pitch. For my part, while I am willing to try to keep people abreast of key players and events in the present crisis, I am trying to be cautious and not speculate in areas about which, as a scholar of the United States, I am not versed. The volume of hate mail about last Saturday‚Äôs letter, pretty evenly divided between those accusing me of backing one side and those accusing me of backing the other, is about the highest I‚Äôve ever received, but I was trying simply to present the verified events of Saturday alone, with a focus on how they affected the United States. While I can‚Äôt say much about the internal meaning of events in the Middle East, I can reflect on what is happening, on a day-to-day basis, in the U.S. in response to the crisis. President Joe Biden has been in touch with Prime Minister Netanyahu throughout the last few days, and this morning met with Secretary of State Antony Blinken, National Security Advisor Jake Sullivan, Principal Deputy National Security Advisor Jon Finer, Homeland Security Advisor Liz Sherwood-Randall, and White House chief of staff Jeff Zientz about the situation, directing them to act with their Israeli counterparts on all parts of the crisis but focusing primarily on the missing hostages. This afternoon, Biden called the leaders of France, Germany, Italy, and the United Kingdom to coordinate support for Israel. After the call, the leaders issued a rare joint statement, expressing ‚Äúour steadfast and united support to the State of Israel, and our unequivocal condemnation of Hamas and its appalling acts of terrorism.‚Äù They reiterated that ‚Äúthe terrorist actions of Hamas have no justification, no legitimacy, and must be universally condemned. There is never any justification for terrorism. In recent days, the world has watched in horror as Hamas terrorists massacred families in their homes, slaughtered over 200 young people enjoying a music festival, and kidnapped elderly women, children, and entire families, who are now being held as hostages.‚Äù They emphasized that their countries would support Israel against such atrocities, and again warned other countries against trying to exploit the chaos after the attack to gain an advantage. At the same time, the statement continued, ‚ÄúAll of us recognize the legitimate aspirations of the Palestinian people, and support equal measures of justice and freedom for Israelis and Palestinians alike. But make no mistake: Hamas does not represent those aspirations, and it offers nothing for the Palestinian people other than more terror and bloodshed.‚Äù The U.S. is facing this crisis with a weakened diplomatic corps, a weakened military, and a weakened government. Because of holds Republican senators have put on the nomination process, the U.S. does not have a Senate-confirmed ambassador to Israel or Egypt, the two countries that border the Gaza Strip. The nominees for U.S. ambassador to Oman and Kuwait are similarly waiting for confirmation, as is the State Department‚Äôs coordinator for counterterrorism. Senator Ted Cruz (R-TX) has held up several of the Middle East nominations, claiming that the ‚Äúnominees keep lying to Congress and the American people, testifying publicly that they are committed to countering Iran and deepening the U.S.-Israel relationship then implementing the opposite policies in secret once confirmed.‚Äù The military is also down critical leaders, as Senator Tommy Tuberville (R-AL) is refusing to lift his hold on more than 300 uncontroversial military promotions, a hold he says is to protest Pentagon policy of permitting military personnel time off to obtain abortion care. 10-10-2020 Three whole years!!! God has been good to us, faithful to us, kind to us, and a teacher to us. It was just this year, earlier this year that Buddy noticed that the hairs on my arms are yellow, golden-yellow, that's how he described them. Beneath the black longer hairs, these golden-yellow tiny sprouts hide, short, noticeable only by very keen observation. Buddy saw it as he studied my skin, a thing he does routinely. Buddy says I'm not fair in complexion, and neither am I light-skinned. He says the perfect description of me is between a smooth light version of Reddish-brown and golden-brown. He says it almost every week, drawing circles around my skin and showing me areas where there's more red than gold, or more brown than both. He'd tease me and call me 'red girl!'Or when we are walking under the sun, he says 'golden girl!' Buddy can't sleep when we are having an unresolved conflict. I can, it seems to be my perfect escape from facing it. I'd wake up in the night and find him tossing and turning or just sitting there looking at me. It's usually at this time that we resolve it, he always speaks first. Always extends the olive branch. 'I know we've just been married for two years, I guess in ten years, you'll be able to speak during a fight.' It's his defense of me not making peace first. Marriage showed me that I'm not as forgiving as I thought I was. Buddy taught me what to do when we are having a conflict and my natural instinct to curl up and hide in my shell comes. He says to come hold him without saying anything. To assure him that he's not kicked out or a stranger. 'I want to be loved, by you! I want to feel that even in a fight,' Buddy is vulnerable with me. He shares his desires freely and in doing so, I've learned to kick the introvert out and reciprocate the same. 'You're so tender, and so innocent' I've heard this every week in this marriage. The Holy Spirit and Buddy have been my teachers in this union. I've been spoiled silly by pampering. Provided for, without asking. Buddy has been so patient with me. So kind to me in my areas of weaknesses. When I've made significant growth, he tells me 'You're learning o! My leadership is working.' Buddy asks me if he's been a good husband. He checks in, eyes moist and expectant of my reply. He tells me to be honest, to tell him where he can improve. In those intimate moments, he lands mine softly, holding me in his arms, showing me how I spoke to him that punctured his ego, sandwiching the not-so-good reviews of my 'wifehood' with the incredible ways I've been a blessing to him. 'There's no other woman for me, I love you and I want you forever, so this marriage must work.' He'll say, on days when the marriage is having a tough day. Then on most days, the sunny days, he'd kiss me and look into my eyes in that tender way he does and say 'You're such a peaceful woman, you give me so much peace and beauty.' And I'd tease him of how his words sound like God describing the Israelites to Ballam, telling him they have no fault while they were giving Moses so much trouble. He'll laugh and say, 'Even your trouble is peaceful.' It was during a conflict that Buddy spoke grammer I didn't understand and I told him 'In this small quarrel we are having, you're speaking big English for me?' His frown grew into a bubble of laughter. I laughed too and as we hugged, I told him 'If I post this on social media, they'll say we are unreal. But the joy and friendship we have in this marriage is so beautiful!' Let's speak another day of how my life has been on a steady growth path since 2018, March when I first met Buddy. How I pray for my single friends that they will experience the kind of love and kindness Buddy gives me. How even our intimate moments reminds me that God heard the prayer I made as I read Francine Rivers redeeming love. And how my mindset and finances have been so expanded by the influence of leadership of this man God blessed me with. We will be married for 90 years. We have 87 to go and I look forward to every minute of doing life with my best friend, personal coach and leader. God keeps us. God honours us. And the children from our womb will take important seats where it matters because they are for signs and wonders. Amen. Happy Anniversary Patrick M. Ndifon II üíû #merpat2020 #JournalOfaJesusGirl

Munroe's book is a valuable resource for anyone who wants to become a more effective leader. Hamas has issued a dire warning, vowing to execute Israeli hostages in response to Israeli bombings. Over 150 hostages, including children and Holocaust survivors, are reportedly held by the terror group, intensifying concerns for rescue operations. You might have noticed my last few posts had a somber tone. No worries -I'm OK! But I want to talk a bit about it. I know that a lot of younger artists have a distorted view of what it means to be a professional artist. I know it because I had it too. After a few years working, and having gone through many ups and downs already, I realize that our patterns and beliefs are very similar. We work hard to convince ourselves that once we reach our goals, we will be happier. Well, reaching goals is great and you definitely need a dream to pursue, of course. You need economic stability and continuity on your job, that's the basics. But after achieving that, there's no plan. Everything pushes you to produce more and faster, to earn more (there's endless bills to pay), to get more satisfaction. And then you might start overworking. Or accepting jobs motivated by economic pressure. Life will happen, and with it, stress, lack of focus and maybe exhaustion. I am writing this because you might feel this way and perhaps you think are alone. There's all these fantastic artists on your feed (you see their work, but you don't really know anything about them) and you feel you are the only one who can't produce great art. Sorry to break the news - we are all in the same boat. It never goes away. To me, this mainly speaks about how much you care about producing art, and the frustration coming from looking at others work, and not yours. The best thing about going through this process (if we can say there's something good about it) is that you learn to navigate it, and there's usually something to learn. The conflict usually comes from a static idea of what do you want to become, sometimes externally imposed. You can change that. You can change who you want to become. You probably have to if you want to be happy.Everyone has a different recipe to get out of the mud, but for me there's a few thoughts that have always helped me: - Focus on the people you care about - that will get the spotlight far from yourself. There's no happiness if they are not there. - Remember why you create art - yes: to feel good. I always feel a bit weird after this long posts (I don't really know anything) but I'll be more than satisfied if this helped anyone in need. Now I'm back to draw a bit. Just for fun. #worldmentalhealthday

The Israeli-Palestinian conflict is a deeply complex and sensitive issue that has caused immense suffering for both sides. Many Palestinians aspire for freedom and self-determination, which is a legitimate aspiration shared by people around the world. It's important to note that not all Palestinians or Palestinian groups can be equated with terrorism. While some individuals and factions, such as Hamas, have been labeled as terrorist organizations by some countries, they also have political and social dimensions that reflect the complexity of the situation. The suffering endured by Palestinians over the years, from the loss of lives and homes to the illegal seizure of their land, is a heartbreaking tragedy that should touch the hearts of people around the world. These are not just statistics; they are stories of families torn apart, dreams shattered, and generations scarred by conflict. The human toll in this ongoing struggle cannot be overstated. It's a stark reminder that behind the headlines and political rhetoric, there are real people, with real emotions, enduring unimaginable pain and hardship. The world must strive for a resolution that ensures justice and a brighter future for Palestinians where the cycle of loss and suffering can finally come to an end. The path to a lasting peace in the region requires dialogue, understanding, and compromise from all parties involved. Ending the cycle of violence and finding a just and equitable solution that respects the rights and aspirations of Palestinians is essential for a better future for all in the region.

On this date in 1981, THE POLICE's fourth studio album GHOST IN THE MACHINE went to No. 1 on the UK Album Chart (Oct 10, 1981) Coming off the heels of their commercially successful Zenyatta Mondatta, Ghost in the Machine saw the band continuing to evolve their sound in new directions, incorporating more keyboards, synthesisers and horns into their music. While remnants of their signature reggae-rock style remained, Ghost in the Machine reflected The Police's desire to embrace the new wave and pop sounds that were dominating the musical landscape in the early 80s. The addition of producer Hugh Padgham, known for his work with Peter Gabriel and Phil Collins, also contributed to the shift in The Police's sound on Ghost in the Machine. Padgham's contemporary 80s production style noticeably differs from the band's previous albums. Employing an experimental recording technique, Padgham had each member - Sting, Andy Summers and Stewart Copeland - record their parts in separate rooms at AIR Studios to capture a live feel. This method of isolating the musicians during tracking allowed for greater flexibility in the mixing process. Lyrically, Sting moved in a more philosophical and politically-minded direction on Ghost in the Machine. The album's title itself comes from the book The Ghost in the Machine by philosopher Arthur Koestler, whose writing was an early inspiration for Sting. Many of the songs touch on weighty themes like economic inequality, consumerism, and living in war-torn environments. This represented a maturation in Sting's songwriting, even if his messages could sometimes come across as preachy. The album kicks off with "Spirits in the Material World," immediately establishing the increased presence of keyboards and synths on Ghost in the Machine. Andy Summers' reggae-tinged guitar licks still peek through, but the central groove is driven by bouncing synth rhythms rather than guitar. Sting's lyrics question institutions and humanity's "troubled evolution," setting the philosophical tone for the rest of the record. "Every Little Thing She Does Is Magic" is an unabashedly pop love song that became one of The Police's biggest hits. The jaunty piano and steel drums provide an upbeat tropical vibe, making the track irresistibly catchy. The song reached No. 1 on the UK Chart, #1 on the Mainstream Rock charts and #3 on the Billboard Hot 100, proving The Police could craft pop perfection without sacrificing their artistic sensibilities. Sting brings in more political themes on "Invisible Sun," reflecting on the grim realities for those living in conflict areas. Summers adds texture with his guitar atmospherics, while the staccato synth melodies provide an ominous undercurrent. The song reached #2 in the UK, though its music video was banned by the BBC for containing footage of Northern Ireland conflicts. The Police bring out the horns in full force on "Hungry for You," with the saxophones even taking over the vocal melody. Sung entirely in French, Sting delivers a steamy lyric over the smoky jazz-pop groove. The horns return on "Rehumanize Yourself" and "One World (Not Three)," giving the album's mid-section a strong ska-pop flavour, though some critics argued this homogenous sound caused the tracks to blend together. Summers provides a standout moment with "Omegaman," a vicious jazz-rocker that is perhaps the best song he contributed during his Police tenure. His overdriven guitar takes centre stage, with no synths or horns to interfere with his gnarled riffs. Sting's lyrics may come across as more philosophical pontificating, but Summer's guitar work is on fire. The Police close Ghost in the Machine with a trio of melodic ballads that return to the darker ambience of the opening tracks. "Secret Journey" makes great use of the Roland GR-300 guitar synth, while "Darkness" is one of the few contributions from drummer Stewart Copeland, who penned both the music and lyrics. Upon its release in October 1981, Ghost in the Machine topped the UK charts and peaked at #2 in the US, spawning the hit singles "Every Little Thing She Does Is Magic," "Invisible Sun," and "Spirits in the Material World." Reviews were largely positive, with Rolling Stone applauding the band's "more commitment, more real anger" on the album. Robert Christgau called it "consistent pleasure" showcasing both their "trickiness and their simplicity." INVISIBLE SUN Everywhere else but in the UK, the first single put out off Ghost In The Machine was the instant, poppy ‚ÄòEvery Little Thing She Does Is Magic‚Äô. For their home base, however, the Police released ‚ÄòInvisible Sun‚Äô but the English media's insidiously subtle self-censorship ensured that the video of the record ‚Äì which contained footage of Northern Irish street carnage of a kind seen most nights on the channel's news programs ‚Äì would keep ‚ÄòInvisible Sun‚Äô off the top of the singles charts and negate the whole point of the group's making the video. text: NATIONAL SECURITY: WE‚ÄôRE MOPPING UP ILLEGAL ARMS, COMMANDER OPERATION SAFE HAVEN TELLS PLATEAU STAKEHOLDERS The Commander Special Task Force Operation SAFE HAVEN (OPSH) and General Officer Commanding 3 Division Nigerian Army (NA), Major General AE Abubakar, has said Operation SAFE HAVEN is seriously mopping-up illegal arms, ammunition and weapons across its Joint Operation Area of Plateau, Bauchi and Kaduna States. The commander made this known today 10 October 2023, during a stakeholders‚Äô meeting held in Mangu town, Plateau State. Addressing stakeholders at the event organised by the Miskhagam Mwaghavul, the Comd OPSH/GOC, said through the meeting, he was convinced Mangu Local Government Area and Plateau State at large would begin to enjoy permanent peace. He maintained that forgiveness was key, in order to end the vicious cycle of violence being experienced in Mangu LGA. General Abubakar disclosed that the triggers of conflict must be adequately addressed by the appropriate authorities, so as to eradicate crisis in the society. While relaying the Chief of Defence Staff and Chief of Army Staff directive that everything legal must be done to stop the circle of violence in Mangu LGA, he called on the people to respect the traditional institution, which is the custodian of peace. He reiterated that the killing of the Ardo of Panyam was a criminal act carried out by a few who would soon be brought to justice. Earlier In their separate remarks, the Emir of Wase, His Royal Highness Alhaji (Dr) Muhammadu Sambo Haruna, Miskhagam Mwaghavul, His Royal Highness Da John Hirse and Chairman Mangu LGA Transition Committee, Honorable Markus Artu, said the meeting was organised to proffer solutions to issues confronting the local government and get everyone onboard in the peace building process embarked upon by relevant authorities. They lauded the Comd OPSH/GOC for his visible contributions and commitment to promoting peace in the State. While underscoring the importance of dialogue in conflict resolution, they appealed to the people to give peace a chance and learn to live with one another. In his vote of thanks, the former Deputy Governor of Plateau State, Professor Sonni Tyoden, thanked the organizers of the event for creating a platform that give parties involved an opportunity to air their grievances and chart a way forward to addressing all issues raised. He further stated the meeting signifies that traditional rulers are the light in their respective communities. Some of the dignitaries present at the meeting include; former Deputy Governor of Plateau State, Professor Sonni Tyoden, Emir of Wase, His Royal Highness Alhaji (Dr) Muhammadu Sambo Haruna, Miskhagam Mwaghavul, His Royal Highness Da John Hirse, Chairman Mangu LGA Transition Committee, Honorable Markus Artu, Member Representing Mangu South in the Plateau State House of Assembly and Chief Whip, Honorable Bala Fwangje. Others include Chairman Miyetti Allah Cattle Breeders Association Mangu LGA, Chairman Mwaghavul Development Association, Chairman Christian Association of Nigeria Mangu LGA amongst others. Highlights of the meeting include comments from dignitaries, fulani/mangu stakeholders and group photographs.

A PRAYER FOR PEACE IN OUR TIMES" - composed by Fr. Peter Scagnelli O God, author and giver of peace, in whose image and likeness each of us has been created with a human dignity worthy of respect on earth and destined for eternal glory, Listen to the cry that rises from every corner of this fragile earth, from our human family torn by violent conflict: Give peace in our time, O good and gracious God, that peace which, as your son Jesus Christ told us and as we have experienced in these days, is a peace which the world cannot give. To world leaders grant the wisdom to see beyond the boundaries of race, religion, and nation to that common humanity that makes us all your children and brothers and sisters to one another. To those who have taken up arms in anger or revenge or even in the cause of justice grant the grace of conversion to the path of peaceful dialogue and constructive collaboration. To the innocent who live in the shadow of war and terror, especially the frightened children, be a shelter and strength, their haven and hope. And to those who have already lost their lives as victims of human cruelty and chemical warfare, open wide your arms and enfold them all in the embrace of your compassion, healing, and everlasting life. Grant this through Jesus Christ, your Son, our Lord. Mary, Mother of all and Queen of peace, pray for us. Amen.

It is world mental health day and as some of you know I have had my issues surrounding mental health. I found out recently that a decade ago I was mis diagnosed with bi-polar disorder and ended up being prescribed with the incorrect (and completely opposite) medication on and off for five years. To be completely honest I wasted years on anti-psychotics allowing social pressure to steer what I was putting into my body. It wasn't until I took complete control of my mental health that things started shaping up for the better. I was also miraculously partnered with a doctor that trusted my request and started combining anti-depressants with anti-psychotics and eventually took me off anti-psychotics all together. My long time friend who is now a doctor in mental health enlightened me recently that it's very likely that I actually have major depressive disorder backed with psychotic features which lines up with my current medication prescription. My suggestion for anyone who is struggling with any mental health related issues is to be vocal about how you are feeling with professionals, friends and family. Transparency about inner conflict be it brain chemistry or mental thoughts is the fastest way to move forward towards maintaining a healthy balance in medication or peace of mind. Also, set goals and work towards completing them, it's rewarding to have something to strive for. If there wasn't struggle there wouldn't be appreciation for peace, completion or joy. Life can be beautiful for everyone. Be strong and assertive, you are not alone in this. - AC #worldmentalhealthday #mentalhealth #bipolar #depression #hope #drtrainhopper #alexandercraig

10 October 2023
Statement Regarding the Terrorist Military Council‚Äôs  Bombing of the Munglai Hkyet IDP Camp near Laiza, Kachin State, Myanmar
1.On 9 October 2023 at 11:25PM local time, the terrorist military council launched heavy artillery and coordinated airstrikes in a Time on Target attack on the Munglai Hkyet IDP Camp near Laiza in Kachin State.

2.Based on initial reports, at least 30 have been killed, including women and 13 children and at least a further 57 have been injured. Rescue and recovery efforts are currently ongoing, and these numbers may increase. In addition, the destruction of one kindergarten, one school, one church and many civilians‚Äô houses have been reported.

3.This deliberate and targeted attack by the terrorist military council on civilians fleeing conflict constitutes a blatant crime against humanity and war crime.

4.The National Unity Government strongly condemns this inhumane crime against humanity and war crime by the terrorist military council, and stands strongly together with the people of Kachin. The National Unity Government shares the pain from this tragic loss of many lives in the Kachin state, and commits to work together to our full ability to restore justice for all those affected.
 
5.The terrorist military council has taken advantage of the moment of the international community‚Äôs attention on the recent developments of the Israel-Hamas conflict to commit yet another crime against humanity and war crime.

6.In accordance with the UN resolution 2669, the National Unity Government strongly urges the international community to take timely and strong actions against the terrorist military council for their crimes against humanity, and to cooperate with the people of Myanmar to  effectively prevent similar atrocities in Myanmar.

‚ùåEXPOSING THE JEHOVAH'S WITNESS CULT
    The Jehovah's Witnesses are a false religious cult which developed out of the unscriptural teachings of Charles T. Russell (1852‚Äî1916). Known at first as the "Russellites," the movement adopted the name Jehovah's Witnesses in 1931 to distinguish the main body from a smaller group which seceded. This smaller group became known as The Dawn Bible Students Association, publishing The Dawn magazine, and sponsoring the nation-wide radio program, ‚ÄúFrank and Ernest.‚Äù

    Charles T. Russell, a Congregationalist, was a former haberdasher in Pittsburgh, who rejected the church's doctrines of Hell and eternal punishment. He fell into a state of unbelief until he came under the influence of the teachings of the Seventh Day Adventists. He began to teach and publish his views, many of which represent a modification of Adventist theology, and are in conflict with many of the major evangelical doctrines of the Christian faith.

    In 1879 he founded his periodical, the Zion Watch Tower (known today as The Watch Tower), which has a wide circulation, and in 1881 organized The Watchtower Bible and Tract Society. He later published his well-known series of books entitled, Studies in the Scriptures. Russell was taken into court on several occasions on various charges: fraudulent dealings in wheat; a divorce suit on grounds of adultery; attempt to avoid payment of alimony; and was accused of perjury and falsehood.

Russell claimed that he alone had the true revelation and that all churches were "the Devil's organization." He continued his unorthodox teachings and campaign against "organized religion" until his death in 1916. He was succeeded as leader of the movement by Judge J. F. Rutherford, who continued the campaign against basic Christian truths, charging that the Christian religion was a fraud. His writings exceeded those of his predecessor, until his death in 1942 from cancer. He was then followed in the Society's presidency by N.H. Knorr.

    Statistics indicate over 8,514,983 Witnesses in 239 countries. There are 117,960 congregations with over 1.3 million Jehovah's Witnesses in the United States. According to a recent estimate, the Jehovah‚Äôs Witnesses are worth approximately $2.1 billion. This includes both their real estate holdings and their investments in various businesses. Jehovah's Witnesses meet in Kingdom Halls (not churches) and consider every member a "minister," all of whom zealously witness to their beliefs. They teach in private homes, witness from house to house, and distribute millions of pieces of the Society's literature.

    The Witnesses believe that all the churches, religion, and all governments are under the control of Satan. Nevertheless, Jehovah has had His Witnesses since the time of Abel, who was His first witness.
    Since Pentecost God has been calling out a special body of 144,000 (Rev. 14) who will rule with Christ as kings and priests during the Millennium and go to Heaven.

    Christ has already returned, according to the Jehovah's Witnesses. He came invisibly in 1874. The beginning of World War I in 1914 marked the time of the beginning of the end of the world (it ended "the times of the Gentiles," Luke 21:24), when nation rose against nation according to Jesus' prophecy in Matthew 24. At this time Satan was expelled from Heaven, and Christ was enthroned. He is now in the process of overthrowing Satan's kingdom on earth (Rev. 11:15). Then in 1918 Christ came to His Temple (Mal. 3:1), which signified His coming to the Jehovah's Witnesses to indwell them as the "temple of the Holy Spirit" (1 Cor. 6:19; 2 Cor. 6:16).

    The Battle of Armageddon is imminent when Christ will finally overthrow the forces of evil and establish His Kingdom. The unsaved dead will be raised and given a "second chance" to accept Christ. All those who do not will then suffer eternal annihilation (not eternal punishment). The special "Bride class" consists of the 144,000 who, after the Millennium, will reign with Christ in Heaven, while the remaining millions of righteous saints will dwell as God's "servants" on the new earth forever.

    In addition to these beliefs, the major doctrines of the cult, which run contrary to the teachings of Scripture, are:

    (1). A denial of the Deity of Christ. Jesus, it is said, was in reality the archangel Michael, a created being. He was not God, nor was He equal with God, according to Jehovah's Witnesses' doctrine. See, however: Micah 5:2; John 1:1; 5:23; 10:30; Philippians 2:5-7; Hebrews 1:8-9; 10-12; Psalm 102:25-27; 45:6-7.

SEVEN WAYS TO PRAY FOR ISRAEL By Derek Prince A little over one hundred years ago, Israel was an insignificant little country in the province of the Ottoman Empire. If the people who were living at that time were told that in one hundred years in the future, Jerusalem would be the center of world attention and conflict, they would not have been able to believe it. This is just one simple example of the amazing accuracy of biblical prophecy. When God‚Äôs timing comes, His word comes into fulfillment. Over the years, many people have expressed their desire to be praying for Israel, but they have not really known how to pray. In this study article I am going to recommend seven ways you can pray for Israel and the situation in the Middle East. 1. Enter Into God‚Äôs Presence With Thanksgiving And Praise It is always appropriate to begin, not with petitions, but with thanksgiving (see Psalm 100:4). Give the Lord thanks for what He has done, is doing and will continue to do for Israel. God has given us a pattern for this in the words of His prophet in Jeremiah 31:7: ‚ÄúSing with gladness for Jacob, and shout among the chief of the nations; Proclaim, give praise, and say, ‚ÄòO LORD, save Your people, the remnant of Israel.‚Äô‚Äù Notice the five actions the Lord tells us to undertake: Sing Shout Proclaim Praise Pray Notice also that prayer comes at the end. One major continuing theme of our thanksgiving to God should be for His covenant-keeping mercy and faithfulness in restoring Israel. As I understand it, at this time in history the number one priority for God is the restoration of Israel. If the amount of space given in the Bible is any indication, there is chapter after chapter dealing with this theme. Furthermore, Scripture makes it absolutely clear that Jesus will not come back until the Jews have been re-established in Israel. There is one person in the universe who hates and fears the thought of Jesus‚Äô return more than anything else: Satan. He is sufficiently acquainted with Scripture to know that if he can frustrate 1) the return of the Jews to their land, and 2) the establishment of Jerusalem as their capital city, then Jesus will not come back. 2. Pray For Israel‚Äôs Salvation If you are only going to pray one prayer, the best one is Paul‚Äôs prayer in Romans 10, verse 1: ‚ÄúBrethren, my heart‚Äôs desire and prayer to God for Israel is that they may be saved.‚Äù If you are not saved, you are lost. There is no middle ground between these two truths. The most important issue for Jew or Gentile is to be saved. 3. Pray For The Release Of The Holy Spirit Upon Israel When you are praying for Israel, don‚Äôt start by focusing on political issues. God often tolerates situations He doesn‚Äôt approve of because He‚Äôs waiting for ‚ÄúHis own special people‚Äù (see Titus 2:11‚Äì14). The only power that will accomplish this is the invisible power of the Holy Spirit. Zechariah 4:6 says: ‚ÄúThis is the word of the LORD to Zerubbabel: ‚ÄòNot by might nor by power, but by My Spirit,‚Äô says the Lord of hosts.‚Äù If it was a question of might or power, God has it all. But might and power‚Äîeven military power‚Äîwill not do what needs to be done to change the hearts of men and women. The only agent that can do that is the Holy Spirit. So the primary necessity is not that the Jewish people have their message preached to them, but rather that the Holy Spirit begins to move upon them and turn their hearts back to God. ‚ÄúThen they will look on Me whom they pierced.‚Äù (Zechariah 12:10) 4. Pray For The Harvest Of The Gentiles Let‚Äôs look at Romans 11:25, which says this: ‚ÄúBlindness [or hardness] in part has happened to Israel until the fullness of the Gentiles has come in. And so all Israel will be saved.‚Äù (NKJV) Paul is saying that all Israel will not be saved until every Gentile, who has been appointed by God for salvation, has come in. If we are truly concerned for Israel, we have a very important reason to be concerned for the salvation of the Gentiles as well. 5. Pray For Godly Leadership The next petition I would suggest is that God will raise up leadership in Israel that will do His will‚Äîpolitical leadership, military leadership, spiritual leadership‚Äî and that He‚Äôll give wisdom to those leaders who are now serving, especially to the Prime Minister. This also relates to the boundaries of the land. I believe we could well pray for God to restore Israel to the boundaries that He has ordained for them at this time. Here is what Psalm 125, verse 3, declares: ‚ÄúThe scepter of wickedness will not remain over the land allotted to the righteous.‚Äù (NIV) I believe that is a scriptural basis for praying Israel back into God‚Äôs program for their ordained inheritance. 6. Stay Within The Parameter Of God‚Äôs Word There is a good deal of praying for the Jews which is sentimental. I don‚Äôt think it accomplishes much. 10 October 2023
Statement Regarding the Terrorist Military Council‚Äôs  Bombing of the Munglai Hkyet IDP Camp near Laiza, Kachin State, Myanmar
1.On 9 October 2023 at 11:25PM local time, the terrorist military council launched heavy artillery and coordinated airstrikes in a Time on Target attack on the Munglai Hkyet IDP Camp near Laiza in Kachin State.

2.Based on initial reports, at least 30 have been killed, including women and 13 children and at least a further 57 have been injured. Rescue and recovery efforts are currently ongoing, and these numbers may increase. In addition, the destruction of one kindergarten, one school, one church and many civilians‚Äô houses have been reported.

3.This deliberate and targeted attack by the terrorist military council on civilians fleeing conflict constitutes a blatant crime against humanity and war crime.

4.The National Unity Government strongly condemns this inhumane crime against humanity and war crime by the terrorist military council, and stands strongly together with the people of Kachin. The National Unity Government shares the pain from this tragic loss of many lives in the Kachin state, and commits to work together to our full ability to restore justice for all those affected.
 
5.The terrorist military council has taken advantage of the moment of the international community‚Äôs attention on the recent developments of the Israel-Hamas conflict to commit yet another crime against humanity and war crime.

6.In accordance with the UN resolution 2669, the National Unity Government strongly urges the international community to take timely and strong actions against the terrorist military council for their crimes against humanity, and to cooperate with the people of Myanmar to  effectively prevent similar atrocities in Myanmar.

GREY JEDI CANNOT EXIST. The idea that they can is rooted in two things: One, a very flawed understanding of what the Force is, and two, a desire to have characters use cool Dark Side powers and yet still be heroes. Both these things are fundamentally incompatible with the way George Lucas constructed the Force. The Force has two sides - the Light, which is compassion, and the dark, which is selfishness. These are broad oversimplifications, but should be sufficient for now. So you ask, why can't you draw on both of them and be even more powerful? Because the Force isn't two sides of a coin - the Dark Side is not the opposite of the Light; it's a corruption of the Light. It's a cancer. The Dark Side of the Force is always there, just as the dark side of human nature is always there. And there is always a struggle between the two - the Dark Side wants to corrupt; the Jedi resists the corruption. He doesn't surrender to it, he doesn't try to use it alongside the light. The Jedi rejects the Dark Side; to do otherwise is to not be a Jedi. But it's not just that it's impossible to draw on the Dark Side and be a Jedi - it's impossible to use the Dark Side at all without being corrupted. Because the Dark Side IS corruption. It's poison; it's cancer. Let me ask you a question: How much cancer should you have in your body to be healthy? The answer, of course, is 'zero'. Does that mean your body is out of balance? No, of course not. It just means you're healthy. It is simply not possible to be healthy when half your body is cancer. It's not possible to be healthy if you have even a little bit of cancer - if you have cancer at all, you are sick. In order to return to health, you have to cut the cancer out. If you don't cut it out, the cancer will eventually overtake your body and destroy you. That doesn't mean that when you're healthy some germs or bacteria or what have you don't still exist - but a healthy body has tools to fight that, to keep it in check. Introduce a cancer into the body, and your ability to fight that sort of thing diminishes. Likewise, if you invite the Dark Side in, your ability to resist anger, aggression, hatred, fear - those things that fuel the Dark Side - diminishes. It inevitably becomes a vicious cycle. So it is with the Dark Side. If it were possible to 'balance' the Force within you in this manner, that would mean that the Dark Side is equal in power to the Light - and that is simply not true. Quicker, easier, more seductive - but NOT as powerful. And NEVER more powerful. George Lucas was very specific in this: Balance, in relation to the Force, means eliminating the Dark Side. The struggle for balance is not trying to make Dark and Light equal, it's trying to eliminate the dark and embrace the Light. But what about Bendu: Bendu doesn't draw on the Dark Side of the Force - or the Light, for that matter. He is unaffiliated. His whole deal was that he refused to take sides. Guess what? Using the Dark Side of the Force IS choosing a side. Bendu doesn't represent a being that simultaneously uses Dark and Light Force, but a character who exists outside of notions of Dark and Light - to quote Dave Filoni, "He likes balance, and he likes neutrality." Neutrality doesn't mean that you work from both sides of a conflict, it means that you choose to work with neither. But what about the Mortis Gods: The Father is the Force in balance - Capable of the Dark, tempted by it, but holding it in check with the Light. This is the natural state of things - balance. The Daughter is the Light Side of Force - the thing the Jedi aspire to and work towards but may never fully attain, an idealized, pure Force, if you will. The Son is the worst-case scenario of what The Force will become if you fully embrace the Dark Side. Since the type of purity represented by the Daughter is unattainable, and the kind of darkness represented by the Son is completely destructive, they are representations of the Force out of balance. But what about Mace Windu using Vapaad: Mace Windu doesn't use the Dark Side when he uses Vapaad; he is strong enough to RESIST using the Dark Side while using Vapaad. That's because he is unusually powerful in the Light, not because he draws on the Dark. He does not let the Dark Side overtake him; he grounds himself in the Light and redirects the Dark. But what about: But nothing. There is no way to use the Dark Side of the Force without being corrupted by it. Not for the Nightsisters, not for the The Knights of Ren, not for the Sith, not for anyone. The Dark Side is corruption - Period. "Once you start down the dark path, forever will it dominate your destiny, consume you it will - as it did Obi-Wan's apprentice." - Yoda "It matters which side we choose. Even if there will never be more light than darkness. Even if there can be no more joy in the galaxy than there is pain. For every action we undertake, for every word we speak, for every life we touch‚Äîit matters. I don‚Äôt turn toward the (truncated)

Long before it was popular to do so, often to the detriment of my career, inter-personal relationships, and being branded Anti-Semitic, I used my voice/platform to publicly advocate for the human rights and self- determination of the Palestinian people. In recent days I have refrained from posting any opinions because I see it as a time of respectful mourning for the Israeli people, as well as all of humanity. The indiscriminate mass slaughter of innocent people by HAMAS is simply too horrific to fathom, too barbaric to justify, too inhumane to rationalize. For those of us who truly care about peace between the Arabs and Jews and wish to see an end to the heartbreaking plight of the Palestinian people, it is our moral duty to condemn acts such as this, that undermine the Palestinian cause. And yes it undermines it because today the people of Gaza have no electricity, water, food, internet etc., and what little is left of their crumbling ghetto exclave, is being bombed while we sit from the comfort of our homes and virtue signal to one another. Just as I have always denounced Israel‚Äôs extremist policies, illegal settlements, and brutal occupation, which has now violently erupted to the surface ravaging both sides, I would be a hypocrite to not publicly condemn the barbaric carnage HAMAS has unleased upon innocent people in Israel, their sheer barbarism in sabotaging the Palestinian cause and committing such atrocities in the name of self-determination and freedom. No amount of mental gymnastics can justify the coldblooded gunning down of 250 innocent young people nor the kidnapping and public desecration of a young woman's almost naked broken body. Those of us who have been advocating for justice, equality, peace and humanity for decades do not need a history lesson about the origins of this conflict, so anyone who wishes to school me can save their time. If you are unable to condemn this massacre by HAMAS, then we are not fighting the same moral fight anyway, for I have always been only on one side, and that is the side of humanity. I am capable of advocating for Palestinian children while denouncing HAMAS, just as I am capable of advocating for Israeli children while denouncing their government. I offer my deepest condolences to the innocent families in Israel who have had their loved ones ripped from their lives, to the Palestinian people who will now pay a great price for HAMAS‚Äô savage act, and to all Jewish people worldwide who share this collective trauma. May we do better as human beings. -Azam

Today's everyday Psychology Tips: Titled: "Understanding the Dynamics of Relationships Through Separation.‚Äú Sometimes two people must fall apart to realise how much they need to be back together again.‚Äù 1. The Value of Space and Distance: It's natural for individuals to need space and distance from one another. Time apart can give a person the clarity they need to honestly evaluate a relationship, allowing them to return with a refreshed perspective. Tip: If you're feeling overwhelmed, consider taking a short break from your partner. Engage in self-reflection and evaluate your feelings with an unbiased mind. 2. Reassess Personal Growth: During a separation, individuals often experience personal growth and change. This growth can either make them more compatible or push them further apart. Tip: Use the time apart to focus on personal development. Dive into new hobbies, read enlightening books, or explore personal passions. 3. Realizing the Absence: Sometimes, absence makes the heart grow fonder. A break from a relationship can help both parties realise what they miss about each other. Tip: List the things you genuinely miss about your partner during your time apart. This can serve as a reminder of why you were together in the first place. 4. Enhancing Communication: Communication breakdowns are a common reason couples separate. Being apart can give individuals the space to improve their communication skills. Tip: Take up courses on effective communication or attend relationship workshops. Reconnecting with improved communication skills can lead to a stronger bond. 5. The Importance of Self-awareness: Separation can lead to a deeper understanding of oneself, allowing one to introspect about individual needs and desires. Tip: Engage in activities that promote self-awareness, such as journaling, meditation, or therapy. 6. Learning from Mistakes: A separation, mainly if it results from a conflict, is an opportunity to reflect on and learn from mistakes. Tip: Instead of dwelling on past mistakes, use them as a learning experience. Discuss them openly with your partner upon reconnection. 7. Strengthening Bonds Through Reconnection: If both parties decide to come back together after a period of separation, the relationship can often emerge stronger than before. Tip: Reconnect slowly. Take things one step at a time, ensuring that old issues are addressed, and both parties are on the same page. Conclusion:Relationships are complex, and sometimes a period of separation is necessary for growth, self-awareness, and, ultimately, reconnection. By using these everyday psychology tips, individuals can make the most of their time apart and potentially come back together more substantially and resilient than before. - Mary Oge Chuks

You might not be familiar with Victor Bockarie Foh. And the Victor Bockarie Foh seen in Freetown is not the same as the Victor Bockarie Foh seen in Limba Bagbo. Limba Bagbo is a small settlement in the Bo District of the Bagbo chiefdom. The former vice president of Sierra Leone during the APC administration came from Limba Former Vice President Victor Bockarie Foh triumphantly transformed Limba village. He built basic amenities for the villagers such as a market, a community hall, a solar-powered light, and so on. He also replaced all thatch roofed structures with zinc roofed structures. That is why he has complete control over his people, and his village people adore him. Victor Bockarie Foh is well-known for creating stunning and beautiful settings. Prior to the conflict, he owned a massive structure known as LAVEEKEE. It was a one-of-a-kind edifice. It was believed that the structure featured more than 20 rooms and a 100-acre well-fenced property. During the civil war, the building was vandalised and was never rebuilt. However, Victor Foh's hamlet Limba has a perplexing name, and many have been trying to figure out where the name "Limba" came from. There is an ethnicity called Limba in Sierra Leone that is not widely apparent in that portion of the country. People have been wondering how the name came to be. I met a man named Smith, who explained to me why the village was named Limba.

With heavy hearts, we reshare this message from UUA President the Rev. Sof√≠a Betancourt, PhD. We lift up her prayer for the people of Israel and Palestine in the face of the most recent and ongoing, devastating conflict: Beloveds, I invite you to stop what you are doing if you can and sit with me in the depth of this tragedy of continued violence between Israel and Hamas. How to reconcile the cost of occupation and of war? How to nuance two very real histories of oppression and violence? I am holding close the words of U.N. Middle East peace envoy Tor Wennesland who said: "This is a dangerous precipice, and I appeal to all to pull back from the brink." We as a people of faith can condemn violence against civilians while at the same time engaging the full legacies and histories of oppression that shape such devastating conflict. As a faith tradition, Unitarian Universalists have long worked for peace, and our principles and values call for the goal of world community with peace, liberty, and justice for all. At the same time, we have not engaged the tangled issues surrounding Israel/Palestine in community since 2018, and our last engagement resulted in severed relationships, and deep pain. I pray for the people of Israel and Palestine. I pray for leaders around the globe who must respond to this latest flare of violence and the untenable ethical considerations that abound. I pray for Muslim and Jewish UUs who experience the impact of this long strife acutely. I pray that those of us less likely to know the trauma of unending brutality and harm will not turn away from generational loss, from the devastating realities and their root causes, or from the relentless tragedy of war and occupation. Be gentle with yourselves when you need to be, but do not turn away unless you must. We are one global family living tenuously on the same human-impacted Earth. Let us center ourselves in justice as we call for peace. We previously discussed the fact that only 28% of adult Americans are considered scientifically literate, which means the majority of adults cannot find, make sense of, and use information about science or technology to engage in a public discussion of policy choices involving science or technology. More concerning is the fact that individuals who are MOST opposed to scientific advances and biotechnology are those that know the LEAST about these topics. Those that know the LEAST about these topics have the greatest disparity in their self-assessed knowledge of those topics. Plainly: these people THINK they know much more about those topics than they do. This overconfidence in knowledge means that these individuals are less likely to listen to credible sources of that information and may be more entrenched in beliefs based on false information. This is routinely illustrated regarding topics such as vaccines, medical interventions, climate change, food ingredients and food safety, agriculture, and more. Indeed, the data demonstrate that individuals who are most opposed to topics such as genetic engineering and GMOs are the ones with the lowest understanding of genetics, molecular biology, biology, and chemistry. However, these are the individuals who believe they know more. For example, the majority of people who are most opposed to genetic engineering technology as it relates to food crops don‚Äôt believe that a regular tomato has genes. Just to be clear: every living organism has genes. This has direct and indirect implications for the health and wellbeing of our society. It means that people who think they understand information they‚Äôre consuming don‚Äôt. That‚Äôs true for everyone: celebrities, media outlets and journalists, politicians, and the public. And this is true across ideologies. Indeed, a bill in California was just signed into law that is in direct conflict with scientific evidence about food ingredients, passed solely due to public pressure and outcry from ‚Äòconsumer advocacy groups‚Äô ‚Äì who are not scientific experts. Science literacy is critical, and without it, we are all at risk of harm to our safety and well-being. Camp near Laiza, Kachin State, Myanmar 1.On 9 October 2023 at 11:25PM local time, the terrorist military council launched heavy artillery and coordinated airstrikes in a Time on Target attack on the Munglai Hkyet IDP Camp near Laiza in Kachin State. 2.Based on initial reports, at least 30 have been killed, including women and 13 children and at least a further 57 have been injured. Rescue and recovery efforts are currently ongoing, and these numbers may increase. In addition, the destruction of one kindergarten, one school, one church and many civilians‚Äô houses have been reported. 3.This deliberate and targeted attack by the terrorist military council on civilians fleeing conflict constitutes a blatant crime against humanity and war crime. 4.The National Unity Government strongly condemns this inhumane crime against humanity and war crime by the terrorist military council, and stands strongly together with the people of Kachin. The National Unity Government shares the pain from this tragic loss of many lives in the Kachin state, and commits to work together to our full ability to restore justice for all those affected. 5.The terrorist military council has taken advantage of the moment of the international community‚Äôs attention on the recent developments of the Israel-Hamas conflict to commit yet another crime against humanity and war crime. 6.In accordance with the UN resolution 2669, the National Unity Government strongly urges the international community to take timely and strong actions against the terrorist military council for their crimes against humanity, and to cooperate with the people of Myanmar to effectively prevent similar atrocities in Myanmar. Record October rain brings floods to southern Myanmar AFP Floods sparked by record October rain hit parts of southern Myanmar on Monday, inundating roads and fields and sending residents fleeing for higher ground. On Sunday authorities reported that 200 mm (almost eight inches) of rain had fallen in the previous 24 hours in Bago region northeast of commercial hub Yangon -- a record for October. The rainy season typically brings months of heavy downpours, but scientists say man-made climate change is making weather patterns more intense. "Most of my belongings are ruined as they are floating in the water in my house," Bago resident Aye Kyi Ma, 47, told AFP from a boat on a submerged street. "Now, I have to stay somewhere else," she said. "There is no electricity and the water is not clean. So we have to buy our meal as we can't cook." Rescuers said they recovered the body of one 60-year-old man in Bago. In Pha Yar Gyi, near Bago, vehicles drove along roads where floodwaters reached bumper levels. Some residents floated along the water on makeshift rafts. "In some places, the tide is as deep as a person's height," Aung Phyo Kyaw, a member of a local rescue team in Bago city told AFP. People had moved to higher land and buildings such as monasteries and homes of their relatives to escape the rising waters, he said. The military and police were also working with rescuers to reach people in flooded areas, he added. The state-backed Global New Light of Myanmar newspaper said the nearby Bago river could exceed its "danger level" by almost a metre in the coming days, warning local residents to take precautionary measures. Flooding began in July and has affected nine of Myanmar's states and regions, including Rakhine, Kachin, Karen, Mon and Chin. Myanmar is in the grip of a bloody civil conflict between the junta, which ousted the government of Aung San Suu Kyi in February 2021, and armed groups opposed to its coup.

Should Christians Support Israel? Christians should definitely support the nation of Israel. We must remember that Israel, the nation, is very special to God. We read in Deuteronomy 7:6-8 these words: "For you are a people holy to the LORD your God. The LORD your God has chosen you out of all the peoples on the face of the earth to be his people, his treasured possession. The LORD did not set his affection on you and choose you because you were more numerous than other peoples, for you were the fewest of all peoples. But it was because the LORD loved you and kept the oath he swore to your forefathers that he brought you out with a mighty hand and redeemed you from the land of slavery, from the power of Pharaoh king of Egypt." God‚Äôs eternal purpose is to bless the world through Israel. Already He has done so in measure, for "salvation is from the Jews" (John 4:22), but the fullness of future blessing is indicated in the wondrous promise of Isaiah 27:6: "In days to come Jacob will take root, Israel will bud and blossom and fill all the world with fruit." The declaration that "salvation is from the Jews‚Äù suggests our immeasurable debt to Israel. All that we have worth having has come to us through the Jews. Our Bible is a Jewish Book, and our Savior is a Jewish Savior. Let us never forget to pray for God‚Äôs chosen people. It is true that Israel, today, is in the place of rejection. The nation is a secular, unbelieving (as to the claims of Scripture and their Messiah, Jesus Christ) nation; but "‚Ä¶at the present time there is a remnant chosen by grace" (Romans 11:5). Some Jews are being saved and are becoming members of the body of Christ through faith in their Messiah. Jews are, biblically speaking, the "chosen people of God" and dearly loved by Him. Another reason for Christians to support the nation of Israel is because of the Abrahamic Covenant. We read of God‚Äôs promise in Genesis 12:2-3, "I will make you into a great nation and I will bless you; I will make your name great, and you will be a blessing. I will bless those who bless you, and whoever curses you I will curse; and all peoples on earth will be blessed through you" (see also Genesis 27:29; Numbers 24:9). One of the United States‚Äô most worthwhile accomplishments has been its consistent regard for the plight of the Jewish nation. No nation in the history of the world has a better record of treating individual Jews with respect than does America. The same can be said for our befriending Israel as a nation. America has committed many sins for which we may well deserve judgment, but as a nation, we have been a consistent friend of the Jews and the nation of Israel, as well as a benefactor. In 1948, President Harry Truman helped persuade the United Nations to recognize Israel as a nation. Since then, the United States has contributed billions of dollars in aid to Israel. From the biblical declarations of God‚Äôs love and care for His chosen people, the nation of Israel, and from the history of nations being destroyed because of their evil dealings with God‚Äôs chosen people, the Jews, Christian believers should give support to the chosen people of God. This is not to say that we necessarily support the methods they use in their relationships with the Arab nations. The Bible warned that conflict would always characterize the relations between the descendants of Isaac and Ishmael. Sadly, this conflict will continue until Jesus comes back to judge the nations and sets up His 1,000-year reign of peace on earth. We must look at the "big picture‚Äù with a biblical worldview. While we do not have to support everything Israel does as a nation, we most definitely should support Israel‚Äôs right to exist. God will fulfill His promises and covenants with Israel. God still has a plan for Israel. Woe to anyone who seeks to defeat that plan; ‚Äúwhoever curses you I will curse‚Äù (Genesis 12:3).

As an organization that has always stood for peace and the protection of human lives, AIESEC International acknowledges our responsibility to address pressing global issues that impact the lives of civilians and infrastructures. We wish to address the ongoing crisis in the Middle East. The situation in this region is a matter of great concern for the international community, and it has been a cause of immense suffering for both the Palestinian and Israeli populations. We want to emphasize that AIESEC stands firmly for peace and the preservation of human lives. The loss of innocent lives, the destruction of infrastructure and continuous violation of human rights are deeply distressing, and we extend our heartfelt sympathies to all those affected by this conflict. Our decision to address this issue is also based on the recognition that this is not only a regional crisis but a pressing global concern. The escalation of tensions in this region has far-reaching implications for international peace and security. By speaking up on this matter, we aim to raise awareness and encourage constructive dialogue that could contribute to a peaceful resolution. In these challenging times, let us remember that our shared commitment to peace is what unites us. We encourage you to engage in respectful and thoughtful conversations with each other, and to always uphold the values of inclusivity, empathy, and the pursuit of a peaceful world.

Considered as a mandala of Shiva, a popular Hindu deity, it represents the field of action of all the vital forces in the universe that Shiva controls and maintains. ‚Ä¢ In an early Hindu form of the game there were four players ‚Äì one for each of the four sides of the board. ‚Ä¢ Fate, as well as logic, had its say in the outcome of the game: at some point participants would roll the dice to determine the order of the moves. The very alternation of black and white in the chessboard squares is a symbol of fate bestowing, in turn, gifts and sorrows. This idea finds its way into the painting with horses at loggerheads in the background and knights fighting fiercely in the name of the king in the foreground. We know how distressing it is to be exposed to images of suffering and violence in war and conflict zones around the world ‚Äì we understand that you may wish to (or need to) turn away. To have compassion during times of crisis, to bear witness to the suffering of others can not only be challenging, but heartbreaking. If you are one of the many caring people distressed by the images coming out of Israel and Gaza right now, you are not alone ‚Äì we see you. We understand the feeling of helplessness upon seeing such devastation and violence unfold through your screens. To feel distressed and overwhelmed by the suffering of others, especially at such a large scale, is to be a caring human. We understand if you need to look away. But we urge you, please don‚Äôt forget them. Active conflict zones are life-threatening for people and animals, but the aftermath can also create long-term dangers like disrupted or diminished food and medical supply, dysfunctional banking systems, and a lack of education and work opportunities, leading to cycles of suffering. When the media spotlight fades, the work of kind-hearted people on the ground during times of war continues. Conflict and ongoing political unrest can create even bigger and longer-lasting animal welfare and humanitarian crises; and for many worldwide this is their daily reality. Many in these regions wake to frightening uncertainty daily, sometimes for years or decades on end. Often it is when the global attention inevitably moves on that the need for support is greatest for the people and animals impacted by conflict and violence. So if you need to look away now, consider making a promise to come back when you are able to and to offer support (in whichever way you can ‚Äî by donating, or by raising awareness & sharing ‚Äî so that the help can flow into areas where it is most needed, for as long as it‚Äôs needed. The ‚Äòeveryday‚Äô impact of war and conflict is gruelling, expensive, and often dangerous. But wherever there is suffering there are people as courageous as they are compassionate ‚Äì whose work on behalf of animals continues day and night, because they know that without them, animals would have no hope. The love and support of this incredible global community is powerful ‚Äì and there are people and animals who are going to need you in the weeks, months and years ahead. So if you must, turn away ‚Äì but please, don‚Äôt turn your back on them forever.

VICTORIAN SOCIALISTS STATEMENT ON PALESTINE Victorian Socialists stand unequivocally on the side of the Palestinian people in their ongoing resistance to Israeli occupation and to the violent repression they‚Äôve been subjected to for more than 70 years. We are horrified that the Israeli military is once again bombing the Gaza Strip and ramping up its war on Palestinians in the occupied West Bank. In just a few days, the Israelis have killed more than 700 people, including more than 100 children. There is now talk of a ground invasion of Gaza, with 300,000 reservists massing ominously near the border. Israeli politicians are preparing for a massacre. Israel‚Äôs Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has threatened to ‚Äúturn Gaza into a deserted island‚Äù. Its defence minister said that they are ‚Äúfighting human animals‚Äù, while another called for ethnic cleansing on the scale of 1948, when 750,000 Palestinians were driven from their homes in a campaign of terror. As if to start this potentially genocidal process, Israel‚Äôs illegal siege on Gaza has now been made absolute: no electricity, food or fuel reportedly will be allowed in. More than 80 percent of Gazans are reliant on foreign aid. How are they supposed to survive this?. This latest round of horror has come about, ultimately, because of the inhuman suffering imposed on the Palestinian people. The media wants us to believe that everything was fine until last weekend. The clear implication is that only Israeli lives matter‚Äîbecause overwhelmingly the Palestinians are the ones being killed year in year out. Over recent decades, Israel has expanded its control over almost every aspect of Palestinian lives. Today, there are 700,000 illegal Israeli settlers in the West Bank, almost triple the number from when the ‚ÄòOslo peace talks‚Äô started in the early 1990s. An ex-Israeli general recently accused the country‚Äôs army of being a ‚Äúpartner in war crimes‚Äù and described the situation there as ‚Äúabsolute apartheid‚Äù. We are appalled and saddened by the loss of civilian lives in this conflict, which over its decades-long course have been overwhelmingly on the Palestinian side. We don‚Äôt accept the idea, widespread in the Western media and politics, that both sides are equally culpable for these deaths. Israel is one of the wealthiest and best armed countries on earth, and enjoys the full military and diplomatic support of the US and its allies. It is committing the crimes of apartheid, occupation and ethnic cleansing. It must be held to account. Recent events are a stark reminder that there cannot be a lasting peace under the current conditions. Peace requires that Palestine be free from the chains of violence and oppression with which Israel keeps it firmly bound. We encourage Victorian Socialists members and supporters to attend upcoming rallies organised by Free Palestine Melbourne in solidarity with the Palestinians and against Israel‚Äôs ongoing bombardment of Gaza: - Tuesday 10 October, 6pm at the State Library, Snap Action: Freedom for Palestine: facebook.com/events/289694640505385 - Sunday 15 October, 12pm at the State Library, Rally for Palestine: facebook.com/events/621858313442265

Gayle and I had quite an ordeal today. But we are safely out of Israel. Had to escape by crossing the Jordan River into Jordan by bus. We went through eight checkpoints at the Jordanian border, and it took over six hours. These people really like their borders. So many machine guns we saw today. At one point, our passports were confiscated, and we were just praying that we would get them back. One of the women in our group was taken out for questioning by a stern and impatient guard. The border was packed with many people fleeing. I especially feel for all the israelis because they were not allowed to cross into Jordan at our checkpoint because of the conflict (Allenby Crossing). We are now staying overnight at a hotel in Amman, Jordan. Tomorrow we are hoping to take a flight to Cairo, Egypt. Through all of this, Gayle and I have had a very strange and powerful peace come over us. Our guides, both Israeli and Palestinian Christians, have been wonderful, with a lot of sharing of common values and faith and love. People really open up when facing a crisis like this, and share very deeply from their souls. The Israelis were taken totally offguard by this attack. To them, it is like Pearl Harbor or 911 to Americans. When one considers the size of their country, it could be considered even worse in proportion. Gayle and I listened to the Sunday service at Swiss while sheltering in our hotel yesterday. We were touched by all the prayers and also when the congregation sang, ‚ÄúGuide Me O Thou Great Jehovah.‚Äù Read over those words again and consider how well they apply to our present lives in light of Chaplain Scott‚Äôs sermon and our situation in the Middle East. I especially like the fourth verse. ‚ÄúWhen I tread the verge of Jordan.‚Äù You did not know it but you were praying for us when you sang that verse. To be clear, we were escaping in the opposite direction, but the words still hold the same meaning. ‚ÄúBid my anxious fears subside. Songs of praises I will ever sing to thee.‚Äù Think of this as you apply Chaplain Scott‚Äôs message from Nehemiah to your own life. God has a call for you. You will face opposition. You must pray. We must be strong in the Lord. We must lift our songs in praise always. 1. Guide me, O Thou great Jehovah, Pilgrim through this barren land; I am weak, but Thou art mighty, Hold me with Thy pow‚Äôrful hand. Bread of heaven, Bread of heaven, Feed me till I want no more; Feed me till I want no more. 2. Open now the crystal fountain, Whence the healing stream doth flow; Let the fire and cloudy pillar Lead me all my journey through. Strong Deliv‚Äôrer, strong Deliv‚Äôrer, Be Thou still my Strength and Shield; Be Thou still my Strength and Shield. 3. Lord, I trust Thy mighty power, Wondrous are Thy works of old; Thou deliver‚Äôst Thine from thralldom, Who for naught themselves had sold: Thou didst conquer, Thou didst conquer Sin and Satan and the grave, Sin and Satan and the grave. 4. When I tread the verge of Jordan, Bid my anxious fears subside; Death of death and hell‚Äôs Destruction, Land me safe on Canaan‚Äôs side. Songs of praises, songs of praises, I will ever give to Thee; I will ever give to Thee. Love and blessings, Pastor Mark and Gayle

In conflict, civilians always pay the highest price.

War is not the answer.

We need peace.

What's happening in Israel and Palestine is a feminist issue. Throughout history, occupation, armed conflict, and terror have had the greatest impact on women and girls.

Since October 7th, 2023, 1,200 innocent Israeli civilians have been killed, with thousands of people injured (AP NEWS). Armed militants raided a peaceful gathering of young people, then abducted grandmothers, mothers, and children from their homes, subjecting them to assault, rape, and murder. Hamas, the group of terrorists funded by the Iranian regime, claimed responsibility. The violence does not start or end with this atrocity; over 560 innocent Palestinian civilians have been killed since the attack, and more will continue to suffer as the Israeli government has cut off water and electricity in Gaza (ABC).

In situations of occupation, armed conflict, and terror, women and girls are more likely to be killed and are often seen as casualties of war. This causes gender-based violence against women to increase in the form of sexual violence, abuse, and torture as weapons of war (UN Women).

We mourn the unnecessary loss of innocent civilian life in Israel and Gaza and place humans, especially women and girls, at the center. In this time of heightened violence, we are holding space for those who are hurting, grieving, and processing this massive loss.

This crisis does not exist in a vacuum and is heightened by years of conflict and long-fought struggles for peace and liberation. It follows 75 years of political failure that leave Palestinians deeply oppressed and Israelis deeply unsafe. As you learn more about the crisis in Israel and Palestine, we encourage you to intentionally seek trusted information, combat misinformation, and denounce antisemitism and Islamophobia.

We must continue to dismantle all systems of oppression that perpetuate violence to reach our collective liberation.

‚ÄòWhat a friendly and forgiving little elephant,‚Äô we remarked when Chemi Chemi came into our care. After everything he had been through, one might assume he would be suspicious or shy, but Chemi Chemi was just eager to be loved. Today, he is back where he belongs ‚Äî living a fully wild life. 
This #SWTTransformationTuesday, discover his story.

RESCUE:  In February 2010, a lone elephant calf was found wandering the fringes of Loisaba Lodge. We will never know exactly how he came to be orphaned, but it was almost certainly by the human hand. Poaching was rife at the time, as was the ever-present challenge of human-wildlife conflict. Lodge staff protected the calf overnight, keeping him warm and showing him kindness. The next morning, he was flown down to our Nairobi Nursery. Because he was found near a small brook, we named him Chemi Chemi, which is a riff on the Swahili word for spring. 

RECOVERY: After a year and a half at the Nursery, Chemi Chemi graduated to our Ithumba Reintegration Unit He made himself right at home in Tsavo. In fact, the afternoon he arrived, he walked directly into a big group of wild bulls, totally undaunted. They all towered over him as he confidently mingled among them, visibly impressed to be amidst such impressive company.

TODAY: In a way, this was a glimpse at his future. Now 14 years old, Chemi Chemi is growing into quite an impressive bull himself. He is now leading a fully wild life, although he continues to visit his human-elephant family at Ithumba. In fact, the final two slides were taken during some of his most recent visits! 

Your support makes these transformation stories possible. To meet the orphans in our care and perhaps support their journey back to the wild through an adoption, tap our link in our bio or visit:

At least 6 Palestinian journalists have been killed in Gaza, 2 more are missing, and 1 has been injured amid the ongoing conflict in Israel and Gaza.

Saeed al-Taweel, the editor-in-chief of Al-Khamsa News, along with two other journalists were killed on October 10 while attempting to film a building in Gaza City, according to Al Jazeera. The crew reportedly received a warning that the building would be bombed, prompting the journalists to stand a safe distance away. However, the attack ultimately hit a different building, which was located closer to the group, killing al-Taweel, Mohammed Subh, and Hisham Alnwajha, Al Jazeera reported.

According to the Committee to Protect Journalists (CPJ), three other Palestinian journalists were fatally shot on October 7 while reporting in the Gaza Strip: Ain Media photographer Ibrahim Mohammad Lafi, Smart Media reporter Mohammad Jarghoun, and freelance journalist Mohammad El-Salhi.

Ain Media photographer Haitham Abdelwahid and Nidal Al-Wahidi, a photographer for the Al-Najah channel, have both been reported missing since October 7, according to CPJ.

Additionally, a correspondent for the Al-Ghad channel named Ibrahim Qanan suffered injuries from shrapnel while in the southern Gaza Strip, Al Jazeera reported.

I've spent the past few days working through my own moral qualms as personally both a pacifist and supporter of nonviolent resistance, and of Palestinian liberation, in light of the events of the past few days. I engaged in this process publicly in my stories, which are now collected in a highlight reel. The issues I raised were important to me (and, I've discovered, many others as well) and also prompted some helpful discussions with people who disagreed with me (some of their responses are also on the reel). For anyone still struggling with this, id suggest checking out that reel. However, I feel that I have been able to work through my own challenges, and am emerging ready to place my full support behind the Palestinian people in their struggle for freedom, however that looks.

In this context, I believe continuing discourse regarding support for hamas or the legitimacy of liberatory violence plays too much into the desired framing of western media, which intentionally uses these questions to distract from the historical context for the violence; the reality of continuous systemic violence perpetrated against the Palestinian people; the power, force, and proportionality assymetries; the explicitly genocidal response from israel; and the immediate needs of the palestinian people for liberation. As one of these memes states, I think the "right side of history" in this conflict is unambiguous, and so the discussion of the appropriateness of violence as a tactic of resistance only muddies water that should be clear.

To be clear, my position is not that I support hamas. Of course I don't. My position is that (1) iit's not my place to second guess if the Palestinian people do, and (2) talking about it is used as a deliberate distraction by western media, and I do not want to play into that framing of what's now happening.

I've also been posting much more heavily to my stories than usual, where you'll find a lot of resources including podcast episodes, videos and links to entire books for those looking to learn more about different facets and the history of the situation.
