You might have noticed my last few posts had a somber tone.
No worries -I'm OK!
But I want to talk a bit about it. I know that a lot of younger artists have a distorted view of what it means to be a professional artist.
After a few years working, and having gone through many ups and downs already, I realize that our patterns and beliefs are very similar.
We work hard to convince ourselves that once we reach our goals, we will be happier. Well, reaching goals is great and you definitely need a dream to pursue, of course.
You need economic stability and continuity on your job, that's the basics.
But after achieving that, there's no plan.
Everything pushes you to produce more and faster, to earn more (there's endless bills to pay), to get more satisfaction. 
And then you might start overworking. Or accepting jobs motivated by economic pressure. Life will happen, and with it, stress, lack of focus and maybe exhaustion.
I am writing this because you might feel this way and perhaps you think are alone. There's all these fantastic artists on your feed (you see their work, but you don't really know anything about them) and you feel you are the only one who can't produce great art.
Sorry to break the news - we are all in the same boat. To me, this mainly speaks about how much you care about producing art, and the frustration coming from looking at others work, and not yours.
The best thing about going through this process (if there's something good about it) is that you learn how to navigate it. The conflict usually comes from a static idea of what do you want to become, sometimes externally imposed. You can change who you want to become. You probably have to if you want to be happy. For me there's a few thoughts that have always helped me:
- Focus on the people you care about - that will get the spotlight far from yourself. There's no happiness if they are not there.
- Remember why you create art - yes: to feel good.
Now I'm back to draw a bit. Just for fun.
#worldmentalhealthday

The Sinai Human Rights Organization, a prominent human rights group, confirmed the Israeli fighter jets' assault, resulting in the closure of the Rafah crossing once again. This closure follows a similar shutdown on Monday when the Palestinian side faced a devastating airstrike, according to a security source cited by AFP.

The situation remains highly volatile as efforts to provide crucial aid to Gaza face significant challenges, raising concerns about the well-being of the people trapped in the conflict zone. Stay tuned for further updates as this situation develops.

We previously discussed the fact that only 28% of adult Americans are considered scientifically literate, which means the majority of adults cannot find, make sense of, and use information about science or technology to engage in a public discussion of policy choices involving science or technology.

More concerning is the fact that individuals who are MOST opposed to scientific advances and biotechnology are those that know the LEAST about these topics. Those that know the LEAST about these topics have the greatest disparity in their self-assessed knowledge of those topics.

Plainly: these people THINK they know much more about those topics than they do.

This overconfidence in knowledge means that these individuals are less likely to listen to credible sources of that information and may be more entrenched in beliefs based on false information.

This is routinely illustrated regarding topics such as vaccines, medical interventions, climate change, food ingredients and food safety, agriculture, and more.

Indeed, the data demonstrate that individuals who are most opposed to topics such as genetic engineering and GMOs are the ones with the lowest understanding of genetics, molecular biology, biology, and chemistry. However, these are the individuals who believe they know more.

For example, the majority of people who are most opposed to genetic engineering technology as it relates to food crops don‚Äôt believe that a regular tomato has genes.

Just to be clear: every living organism has genes.

This has direct and indirect implications for the health and wellbeing of our society. It means that people who think they understand information they‚Äôre consuming don‚Äôt. That‚Äôs true for everyone: celebrities, media outlets and journalists, politicians, and the public. And this is true across ideologies. Indeed, a bill in California was just signed into law that is in direct conflict with scientific evidence about food ingredients, passed solely due to public pressure and outcry from ‚Äòconsumer advocacy groups‚Äô ‚Äì who are not scientific experts.

Science literacy is critical, and without it, we are all at risk of harm to our safety and well-being.

What Happened: The United Arab Emirates (UAE) issued a statement on October 8, 2023, strongly condemning the actions carried out by the Palestinian Islamist group Hamas against Israeli towns. The statement from the UAE's foreign ministry characterized these actions as a "serious and grave escalation" in the ongoing conflict.

Details: The UAE's foreign ministry expressed deep concern over reports of Israeli civilians being abducted from their residences, describing such acts as "appalling." The ministry emphasized the importance of upholding international humanitarian law, stressing that civilians on both sides should be protected and should never be targeted in any conflict.
This condemnation from the UAE comes amid a significant shift in the Middle East's geopolitical landscape. In 2020, the UAE made history by becoming the first Gulf nation to establish diplomatic ties with Israel, marking a departure from the longstanding Arab stance on the Palestinian issue.

More: The UAE's denouncement of the Hamas attacks holds particular significance due to the evolving dynamics within the Middle East. Over recent years, the UAE and Israel have been discreetly aligning their interests, largely driven by shared concerns about common regional threats. The UAE's vocal support for Israel in the current crisis underscores the growing convergence of interests between these two nations.
The UAE's response also highlights its emerging role as a prominent player in the Middle East. Traditionally, the UAE has maintained a relatively low profile in international affairs. However, its condemnation of the Hamas attacks demonstrates a newfound willingness to take a clear stance on contentious issues and actively shape regional dynamics.

‚ÄºÔ∏èMANIPUR: In a recent barbaric incident, a video purportedly went viral showing a man being burned in Manipur on Monday.

Tribal organizations condemned the cruelty and demanded the government take action, saying it was linked to the incident in which two women were displayed n@ked. [PTI]

Meanwhile, the video of the burning man was shot on May 4, the same day that two women were paraded n@ked by a mob, eliciting widespread outrage when it was revealed in July. The ethnic conflict in Manipur began on May 3.

On Sunday, many individuals on social media shared a seven-second video of a man, apparently dead, wearing a black T-shirt and camouflage trousers being burned, while remarks in a local language and gunshots can be heard in the background.

"We investigated the incident and discovered that it occurred on May 4." The corpse has been identified and is currently being treated at a hospital. It is related to the incident in which two women were displayed naked," said Security Advisor Kuldeep Singh. [PTI]

He added that the deceased was from a village in the Kangpokpi district but did not specify where the incident occurred.

The Indigenous Tribal Leaders' Forum (ITLF), a conglomeration of Manipur's recognized tribes located in Churachandpur, also condemned the "shocking and barbaric incident" on Monday.

On the other hand, the Kuki-Zo community has been advocating for the tribe to have its own governance.

Following the violent clashes between Meiteis and tribals, eleven tribal MLAs from Manipur's Chin-Kuki-Mizo-Zomi group have urged that a separate government be established for their tribe. However, Chief Minister N. Biren Singh has refused the demand.

Furthermore, more than 180 people have been killed since May 3, when a 'Tribal Solidarity March' was held in the hilly areas to resist the Meitei community's quest for Scheduled Tribe (ST) status.

‚ÄúOne day I was on the StairMaster, doing my thing, when a Black gym employee approached a white guy on the treadmill in front of me and told him to pull his mask back up. He gave her a quick glance, slowly tugged the fabric, then returned his focus to running,‚Äù writes HuffPost guest writer Delano Burrowes.‚Å†
‚Å†
‚ÄúThere was something about the look I saw him give her: entitlement. Dismissal. Invisibility. It triggered an overwhelming urge in me to wipe the smugness off his face.‚Äù‚Å†
‚Å†
‚Äú‚ÄòHey! Didn‚Äôt she tell you to put your f**king mask on?‚Äô‚Äù I was somehow off the StairMaster, standing next to the man, and speaking at a volume I never used.‚Äù‚Å†
‚Å†
‚ÄúI expected, wanted, and needed an apology ‚Äî for so much. Instead, I got a version of the glance he‚Äôd given the employee. I wasn‚Äôt about to let it end like that, but then I saw past him to the mirror behind the treadmills. I looked crazy.‚Äù‚Å†
‚Å†
‚ÄúHow did I become this person? I asked myself. Yeah, he‚Äôs probably an a**hole, but gyms are full of a**holes. So what?‚Äù‚Å†
‚Å†
‚ÄúAfter the treadmill interaction, I thought about another gym incident, also regarding a mask, a few months before. I was in the weight room when I heard, ‚Äú‚ÄòHey, bro, can you put your mask over your nose?‚Äô‚Äù‚Å†
‚Å†
‚ÄúThe Black guy on the butterfly machine looked over at the white guy talking to him. ‚ÄúNah. I‚Äôm good,‚Äù he said.‚Äù‚Å†
‚Å†
‚Äú‚ÄòHuh? You do know there‚Äôs a pandemic, right?‚Äô the white guy asked.‚Äù‚Å†
‚Å†
‚ÄúIt escalated into an adrenaline-fueled argument, and a Black staffer was asked to intervene.‚Äù‚Å†
‚Å†
‚ÄúI knew the conflict going on in the staff member‚Äôs head: 'How can I side against another Black person in this space?' They averted their eyes and walked away.‚Äù‚Å†
‚Å†
‚ÄúI had barely talked to the other Black guy in all the years I‚Äôd seen him around, but now we looked at each other and slowly nodded.‚Äù‚Å†
‚Å†
‚ÄúWhy did I act like that then and now had a completely opposite reaction? It made no sense, except it did.‚Äù‚Å†
‚Å†

SGT Ryan Pedder teamed up with SGT Connor O‚ÄôNeill and FSGT Ryan Hodgson to facilitate the Building Blokes program for aviators from 2 Operational Conversion Unit at RAAF Base Williamtown.

After seeing many young men struggling with numerous issues, such as poor resilience and issues propelled by social media, the team collaborated with the Top Blokes Foundation, a not-for-profit mental-health charity.

Aimed at improving the mental health and well-being of young men, the Building Blokes program was delivered over eight weeks in two-hour workshops on topics like body image, sexual health, budgeting, conflict management, leadership and nurturing healthy relationships.

This October the squadron is participating in the Top Blokes‚Äô Lift the Load Challenge, which involves wearing a 10kg weighted vest across 50km throughout the month, to raise funds for young men‚Äôs mental health.

#WMHD2023 is a reminder to all of us to seek help early for any mental health challenges we might be facing, and encourage our colleagues, friends and family to do likewise.

Apartheid, a system rooted in the practice of systematic racial segregation and discrimination, has historically been proven to breed conflict, resentment, and violence. Its legacy in South Africa serves as a testament to the profound societal rifts and injustices it generates. Now, applying such a system to the already volatile context of Palestine is a recipe for intensifying the strife. The Palestinian-Israeli conflict is underpinned by deeply rooted historical grievances, territorial disputes, and religious significance. Layering an apartheid system onto such a landscape only exacerbates feelings of dispossession and disenfranchisement among the Palestinians, who would view this as a further erosion of their rights, identity, and connection to their homeland. 
At its core, apartheid negates the concept of coexistence, and instead fosters division. In a land as historically interconnected as Palestine, where various religious and ethnic communities have coexisted for millennia, the imposition of apartheid would be antithetical to any prospect of peace. Such a system would not only alienate and marginalize the Palestinian population, but also the international community, many of whom view apartheid as a grave violation of human rights.
Moreover, peace thrives on mutual respect, understanding, and dialogue. Apartheid, by design, is the antithesis of these principles. Instead of fostering communication and bridging divides, it creates physical and psychological barriers. The walls and checkpoints that might proliferate under such a regime in Palestine would be constant, grim reminders of division and inequality. Every day, as Palestinians navigated this oppressive landscape, the chances of reconciliation would recede further into the distance. The takeaway is clear: Apartheid, a system that institutionalizes division and discrimination, will never pave the way to lasting peace in Palestine or anywhere else. It will only sow seeds of anger, despair, and resistance, perpetuating a cycle of conflict for generations to come.

Molotov man, 1979

This famous picture was taken during the Nicaraguan Revolution in 1979. The Nicaraguan Revolution was a civil war in Nicaragua in Central America that lasted from 1961 - 1979. It was a conflict that was fought between communist rebels called the Sandinistas and the dictatorship at the time, which was called the Somoza regime. In the image, Pablo "Bareta" Arauz throws a Molotov at a Somoza National Guard garrison. This image was taken right at the end of the war. The fort was one of the last strongholds of the Samoza regime.

The civil war was a Sandinista victory and saw a communist overthrow of Somoza's rule in Nicaragua. However, the Civil War then transitioned to a period known as the Contra War. This saw US-backed right-wing rebels called the Contra rebels against the Sandinista regime. This occurred during what many historians would consider the second height of the Cold War when the US-sponsored different groups worldwide who rebelled against communist regimes in other countries. These wars are called "Proxy Wars" and were common throughout the Cold War. 

The Contra war has different start and end dates depending on who is asked. However, it is generally agreed upon that it has its roots in the late 1970s and ended in the early 1990s. The Contra war resulted in the Sandinistas being voted out, and a more democratic government was formed. The two phases of the conflict (the Civil War and the Contra War) saw Nicaragua at war for nearly 30 years.

I‚Äôve been walking for miles through London today, looking up at the skies, whenever I have felt my heart pounding about the escalating terror of the news. I thought about my Jewish grandmother, who escaped the persecution and pogroms of Eastern Europe when she came to study music in London as a young student, and in doing so, was saved from the fate that engulfed so many of her relatives. I remembered my own childhood in this city - and all the ways in which different nationalities and religions have found themselves able to co-exist - even through successive episodes of conflict, distrust or suspicion.
And this evening, whenever I descended into despair at the toxic hatred expressed by anonymous strangers on social media, I made myself stop reading their poisonous words, and look up at the sky again. This sky that encompasses all of us; this sky that has seen bombs fall on the innocent, and thunderstorms rage; this sky that is beyond our comprehension and yet still offers comfort, even in the darkness, spinning through an infinite and unknowable universe.
I am yet again struggling to find the words to express my profound sadness, but the sky says it all, silently‚Ä¶
So I‚Äôm thinking of everyone who is grief-stricken tonight, and hoping that you may feel a little less alone, in the knowledge that many of us are also searching for meaningful ways to share our tangled, jagged emotions, in this beautiful, broken world‚Ä¶

We know how distressing it is to be exposed to images of suffering and violence in war and conflict zones around the world ‚Äì we understand that you may wish (or need) to turn away. To have compassion during times of crisis, to bear witness to the suffering of others can not only be challenging, but heartbreaking.

If you are one of the many caring people distressed by the images coming out of Israel and Gaza , you are not alone ‚Äì we see you. We understand the feeling of helplessness upon seeing such devastation and violence unfold through your screens.

We understand if you need to look away. But we urge you, please don‚Äôt forget them.

Active conflict zones are life-threatening for people and animals, but the aftermath can also create long-term dangers like disrupted or diminished food and medical supply, dysfunctional banking systems, and a lack of education and work opportunities, leading to cycles of suffering.

When the media spotlight fades, the work of kind-hearted people on the ground during times of war continues. Conflict and ongoing political unrest can create even bigger & longer-lasting animal welfare and humanitarian crises. For many this is their daily reality. Many in these regions wake to frightening uncertainty daily, sometimes for years or decades on end.

Often it is when the global attention inevitably moves on that the need for support is greatest for the people and animals impacted by conflict and violence. So if you need to look away now, consider making a promise to come back when you are able to and to offer support in whichever way you can so that the help can flow into areas where it is most needed.

The ‚Äòeveryday‚Äô impact of war is gruelling, expensive, and often dangerous.

But wherever there is suffering there are people as courageous as they are compassionate ‚Äì whose work on behalf of animals continues day and night, because they know that without them, animals would have no hope.

The love and support of this incredible global community is powerful ‚Äì and there are people and animals who are going to need you in the weeks, months &  years ahead.

So if you must, turn away ‚Äì but please, don‚Äôt turn your back on them forever.

Church family,
 
Like many of you, we have watched the horrible attacks of Hamas against Israel over the weekend. The brutality we have all witnessed on our TVs and phones represents the very evil the kingdom of Christ seeks to drive out. We are continuing to monitor ways in which we might be of assistance to partners via our Compassion Offering. 
 
As the people of God, we think it‚Äôs vital to intercede in prayer in times of crisis. This weekend, we will take time in each of our services to do just that. We believe wholeheartedly that our God is moved by the prayers of His people, and we invite you to join us as we pray during this ongoing conflict. Thank you for joining us. 
 
 Psalm 34:15‚Äì18 ESV:

15 The eyes of the Lord are toward the righteous and his ears toward their cry. 

16 The face of the Lord is against those who do evil, to cut off the memory of them from the earth. 

17 When the righteous cry for help, the Lord hears and delivers them out of all their troubles. 

18 The Lord is near to the brokenhearted and saves the crushed in spirit.

It is very difficult to find the right words (any words) for last weekend‚Äôs events. And those of us in the West who cannot ever pretend to understand what it‚Äôs like to live daily in the shadow of one of this world‚Äôs oldest, bitterest, and most historically nuanced disputes should choose our words with utmost care. 
On a personal level, I am particularly shaken by the atrocity at the Supernova festival, as it happened close to an event location I have DJed at before and was in fact due to play again next month. Horrific scenes and haunting images that are extremely hard to process. My sincerest condolences go out to all the friends and families of the innocent victims of this and the other brutal barbaric attacks and hope and pray that the missing and those currently being held captive are quickly found or released without any further trauma. 
It‚Äôs also distressing to know that there will be so many more innocent victims on both sides of this ongoing conflict. The suffering is truly heartbreaking. It‚Äôs now likely that thousands of innocent Palestinians will also lose their lives in retribution.
I am also not ignorant to the daily suffering over many years of those who live in Gaza and the West Bank; and that for them, being able to enjoy any kind of party scene is, along with many other freedoms most of us are lucky enough to be able to take for granted, a very distant dream.
For those of us who have lived our lives in a global dance music community rooted in love and positivity, to see it strike at the heart of our scene, to innocent party goers doing what we all love doing week in week out, verges on incomprehensible.
The whole thing is a ghastly stain on humanity. For a species that considers itself to be so smart, enlightened and superior, we can be so monumentally stupid and evil.

There are a lot of people online talking about the Israel-Palestine conflict right now. People are picking sides (because that's what we do). Israeli forces have ramped up attacks following an attack from Hamas. Netanyahu is promising that his response will change the future of the occupation and conflict. But, Palestinian resistance forces and Hamas have never had the military power or global support Israel has. Nor have the Palestinian people currently living on occupied lands on the Gaza Strip ever really had freedom of movement and safety (or nationhood) they deserve. We are watching genocide happen.

People are using ideological shortcuts to determine when violence is justified, necessary, or warranted.

Rather than enter a political debate that predates me and that I have not, myself, participated in organizing around, I would rather just focus on the ways that we condone violence and genocide when powerful people, institutions, and nations suggest its the only way forward. 

We hold space for violence when it's enacted by countries with asymmetric military power, nuclear arms, and political cache among other developed nations. We are fine with violence when it preserves the status quo and keeps our existing political relationships intact.

It's only when marginalized and oppressed people defend themselves that we see calls to end the violence. Protestors are cast as aggressors when their goal is merely survival. 

This is the colonial project at work. Notice it. Call it out. There are people who cannot speak in this moment. 

This is not about our political beliefs and sides. It's about the belief that human beings deserve to live and live fully.

Tweet grabs: Whenever Black and Brown people resist oppression, we are cast as violent, aggressive, and riotous. But, the oppressors are silent about the violence they've enacted, typically for generations.

This is how colonization works. Rewriting history is central to this process.

When you chastise oppressed people for resisting because "it will make things harder for them," you're siding with the oppressors.

Roof knocking is a term used by the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) and others to describe the practice of dropping non-explosive or low-yield devices on the roofs of targeted civilian homes as a prior warning of imminent bombing attacks to give the inhabitants time to flee the attack.

The practice was employed by the IDF during the 2008‚Äì2009 Gaza War, Operation Pillar of Defense in 2012, and Operation Protective Edge in 2014 to target the homes of police officers or Hamas political or military leaders.

During the October 2023 Gaza‚àíIsrael conflict a strike by IDF on a high-rise building in Gaza reportedly also came after roof knocking.

Other countries including the US have used the practice.

Historically leaflets were used to warn citizens of imminent strikes or combat and to evacuate the area immediately. 

Technology has allowed the use of mass text messages to deliver similar messages as well.

In 2015 I had the opportunity to visit the Holy Land with a group called @thetelosgroup. The work of Telos is to work towards peace. For the week I was there we met with both Israelis and Palestinians on different sides of the conflict. We shared meals, heard their stories and I very quickly became overwhelmed with just how complicated and divisive the conflict is. I also realized as an American, who is of Jewish descent, proud of my Jewish heritage and in love with the Jewish people, just how little I understand of those complexities. A day that changed me forever was when I joined a group of women to make jam. Before we got into the kitchen we sat in a circle and listened to these women share about why they gather. It all started when an Israeli woman who had been taught to hate Palestinans, lost her son at the hands of a Palestinian, and a Palestinian woman, who had been taught to hate Israelis, lost her son at the hands of an Israeli, said ‚Äúno more!‚Äù. They meet each other in their shared grief and committed to seeing humanity in each other and in each other‚Äôs people. They learned there were more people like them, finding each other's humanity in the brokenness the hatred had caused. And they gather, and they share their stories and they make jam and they work towards peace. Look, what is happening in the Holy Land is a literal nightmare. The history and complexities and the lies and the hate and the fear are overwhelming. It is hard to have hope. I am the first to say I do not understand. I also know that in my ignorance, I do not want to further perpetuate hate and othering. So as I fall on my knees and pray for the people in Israel and Palestine and for the terror to end, my prayer is for peace and for the miracle of the recognition of our collective humanity. As simple and complex and ignorant as that may be.

Yoga scriptures, such as The Yoga Sutras and the Bhagavad Gita, taught me that God is omnipresent, transcending physical limitations and permeating the entire universe. Judaism also acknowledges the concept of God's omnipresence, emphasizing that it extends beyond physical space to encompass the spiritual and metaphysical realms.

In the face of unimaginable and TRAGIC events, like the *recent* Afghanistan & Moroccan earthquakes that claimed thousands of lives, as well as acts of terrorism like the unprecedented Hamas attacks in Israel, to include the innocent lives lost in Palestine, so it is natural to wonder and question the presence of God. My heart is with all the innocent lives taken and the families suffering and in pain. üíî<These events are widely discussed on social media.>

The Israel-Palestine conflict is a complex issue, intertwined with DEEP religious, political, and territorial disputes that have spanned ***generations.*** While I am not an expert on this historical context, it raises the question: where is God in all of this?

The absence of divine intervention to prevent wars, natural disasters, deadly diseases such as cancer, starvation and heinous crimes like child and sex trafficking can be extremely disheartening. It is difficult to find answers in the face of such evil, adharma, hatred, FEAR and loss.

In the darkness, there are glimpses of hope. I find the presence of God in the hope for a better future for our children and the next generation. I see God in the aspiration for peaceful resolutions to conflicts between nations. I find solace in the hope that truth & LOVE will ultimately prevail. And I believe in the inherent ability of Mother Earth to heal and repair herself.

You guys will have your own personal views and reasons for either liking or disliking these sentiments, I wanted to share my perspective. It is a reminder that even in the face of immense challenges, there is always room for hope, resilience, and the potential for positive change.

üéØWhat is Israel-Palestine Conflict?

The Israel-Palestine conflict is one of the world‚Äôs longest-running and most controversial conflicts. It is a conflict between two self-determination movements- the Jewish nationalist project and the Palestinian nationalist project, in the same territory.

üéØHistorical Timeline of Israel-Palestine Dispute

1) 1947 - United Nations adopted‚ÄØResolution 181 known as the Partition Plan.

2) 1948-49 :- First Arab Israel War

3) 1964 :- Formation of Palestine Liberation Organisation (PLO)

4) 1979 :- Camp David Accords signed between Egypt and Israel.

5) 2008 :- Beginning of Israel Hamas wars. Three wars were faught in 2008, 2012 and 2014.

üîÜ Important Areas

1. Gaza Strip :- Hamas rules over Gaza. Gaza‚Äôs borders are tightly controlled by Israel and Egypt. Gaza has been  under Israeli sea and air blockade since 2007.

2. West Bank :- According to the Oslo accord ,the occupied West Bank was divided into three areas ‚Äì Area A(Under Palestinian control), Area B(Under Joint control) and Area C(Under Israeli control). Control of areas had to be gradually transferred from Israel to Palestine. However Israel has been construction Separation Walls, Increasing the security checkpoints and allowing illegal settlements in these areas. Israel has been increasing its hold over the West Bank.

3. Jerusalem :- West Jerusalem has been Israeli territory since 1948 with Jews in the majority. East Jerusalem, which houses the Old City of Jerusalem including the Al-Aqsa Mosque compound, is Palestinian majority and was occupied by Israel in 1967.The whole of Jerusalem is claimed by Israel as its capital. Palestinians claim East Jerusalem as the capital of a future Palestinian state.

In hindsight, the drivers of Hamas‚Äôs startlingly well-planned, land-sea-air attack on Israel on Saturday were in plain sight.

The operation reflects a pattern of four wars and regular outbreaks of violence between Israel and Hamas militants in Gaza since 2005, when Israel withdrew its military posts and forcibly removed 9,000 Israeli settlers from the territory.

Each time Hamas has launched rockets at Israel or engaged in similar provocations, it has drawn heavy retaliation from Israel in the form of major bombings on the Gaza Strip. Hamas, however, seems to regard this as a cost of doing business.

An important factor motivating Hamas towards violence is that it has to watch its flanks. Other smaller, but increasingly extremist groups, are contesting its authority in Gaza, notably Palestinian Islamic Jihad.

These groups have, at times, independently launched rocket attacks on Israel, which bring retribution on the whole territory.

On top of this, the Israeli government formed by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu last December is the most right wing in Israeli history. This government has made no secret of its desire to annex the West Bank and has permitted significant expansion of Jewish settlements in the territory, which are illegal under international law.

That has led to conflict between settlers and young West Bank Palestinians, who in the past year have formed a loose grouping known as the ‚ÄúLions‚Äô Den‚Äù.

A row between the Celtic board and a section of supporters over the Middle East conflict looks set to run after a fan group hit back at the club.

Celtic earlier condemned banners which were displayed in the standing section at their stadium during Saturday's win over Kilmarnock.

But the Green Brigade have now called on supporters to display Palestine flags during their upcoming Champions League game against Atletico Madrid as Israel continues its airstrikes and blockade of Gaza.

Celtic's Israel international, Liel Abada, meanwhile, issued thanks to those who had sent messages of support in the wake of the Hamas attack on his country.

Abada's Israel and former Celtic team-mate Nir Bitton had hit out at supporters on Saturday after they flew flags and displayed banners which read "Free Palestine" and "Victory to the Resistance".

The club issued a statement on Monday which condemned and disassociated themselves from the banners.

A statement added: "Celtic is a football club and not a political organisation. One of our core values from inception is to be open to all regardless of race, colour, politics or creed.

"That is why the club has always made clear that political messages and banners are not welcome at Celtic Park, or any match involving Celtic.

"At a time of loss and suffering for many, it is entirely inappropriate for any group of individuals to use Celtic Park as a vehicle for such messages.

"We call on all supporters, regardless of their personal views, to unite in backing our players and the club while respecting the rights and beliefs of others; particularly those whose lives are affected by violence and hatred.

‚ÄòThe last of Cato‚Äôs public services is said to have been the destruction of Carthage. It was actually Scipio the Younger who completed the work, but the war was undertaken mainly on the counsel and advice of Cato.

Cato was sent to the Carthaginians and Masinissa the Numidian, who were at war with each other, to inquire into the reasons for their conflict.

Finding, that the city was not, as the Romans thought, in a poor and unprosperous state, but well populated with good fighting men, teeming with immense wealth, and not a little proud of this, Cato thought that it was not the time for the Romans to be organising the affairs of the Numidians and Masinissa; rather, if they did not now put a stop to the city which had always been their most hostile enemy, they would once more be in danger as great as before.

Cato quickly returned to Rome and advised the senate that the former defeats of the Carthaginians had lessened not so much their power as their foolishness, and that these were likely to make them in the end not weaker, but more skilful in warfare, while their conflict with the Numidians was a prelude to conflict with the Romans, and peace and treaty were just names for a war which was waiting for a suitable opportunity to arise.

Additionally, it is reported that Cato arranged to drop a Libyan fig in the senate when he shook out the folds of his toga. To the senators who admired its size and beauty, he remarked that the country where it grew was only three days sail from Rome.

In one respect he was even more violent, in that, whenever he gave his vote on any issue whatever, he would add the words: ‚ÄòIn my view Carthage must be destroyed!. In this way Cato is said to have brought about the third and last war against the Carthaginians.‚Äô Plutarch Life of Cato the Elder 26‚Äì27.4üìó‚úç

UN Secretary-General Antonio Guterres on Monday called for an end to ‚Äúthis vicious circle of bloodshed, hatred and polarization,‚Äù as the conflict between Hamas and Israel continued for a third day.

He repeated his condemnation of ‚Äúthe abhorrent attacks by Hamas and others‚Äù on Israeli towns and villages, launched from Gaza, which have left more than 800 Israelis dead and more than 2,500 injured since they began on Saturday.

‚ÄúI recognize the legitimate grievances of the Palestinian people but nothing can justify these acts of terror and the killing, maiming and abduction of civilians,‚Äù Guterres said as he reiterated his call for an immediate halt to the attacks and the release of all hostages.

He acknowledged that the violence does not exist ‚Äúin a vacuum‚Äù but stems from a ‚Äúlong-standing conflict with a 56-year-long occupation and no political end in sight.‚Äù

He added that he was ‚Äúdeeply distressed‚Äù by the decision of Israeli authorities to respond to the attacks by imposing a total siege on Gaza, which has already been under blockade since 2007.

In the intricate web of trade between India and Israel, cut and polished diamonds have long occupied a prominent position. India's exports of these exquisite gems to Israel, valued at approximately $1.2 billion, constitute a vital segment of their economic exchange. Following closely behind is the trade in lab-grown diamonds.

Conversely, India primarily imports rough diamonds from Israel, with rough diamond imports amounting to $519 million and cut and polished diamond imports at $220 million, according to a report by PTI.

However, the ongoing Israel-Hamas conflict threatens to cast a dark shadow over this lucrative diamond trade.

Colin Shah, Managing Director of Kama Jewelry, spoke to PTI about the potential adverse impact of the conflict on Indian exports to Israel. He noted that the war situation could further exacerbate challenges in the trade relationship between Israel and its second-largest trading partner in Asia- India.

In the fiscal year 2022-23, the total gems and jewellery trade between India and Israel amounted to $2.04 billion, a decline from the $2.8 billion recorded in the previous fiscal year. Exporters are wary that the Israel-Hamas conflict may further disrupt this trade.

Sharad Kumar Saraf, the founder chairman of Technocraft Industries India, based in Mumbai, highlighted the conflict's potential short-term effect on Indian exporters due to the conflict, saying an escalation could make things a lot harder for exporters in the region.

Ajay Srivastava, co-founder of GTRI, warned that trade could face significant disruptions if operations at Israel's three largest ports‚ÄîHaifa, Ashdod, and Eilat‚Äîare affected.

The majority of India's merchandise trade with Israel is routed through the Eilat port, strategically situated on the Red Sea, PTI reported.

‚ÄúI‚Äôm fine‚Äù is short, sweet and very easy to say all the time. But am I really fine? Can I be fine mentally, emotionally or spiritually 24x7?
There may be ample of reasons for not being okay but we can hardly say so and deal with it all alone. And it can push you to an unknown world of darkness making you depressed or anxious. What if you have thoughts of ending it all?

Sorcerer is now a fantastic book: part script, part novel, part manual, and replete with appendices and drawings. It'll be published on November 8 and is available to pre-order now from @prototypepubs Scroll down for some event information. @stevenzultanski and I are terrifically proud of it.

‚Äî‚Äî

Three friends hang out and share a long and unremarkable conversation about getting dressed, headaches, ticks, compression fantasies, surgery, and personal aspirations, among other things. When two of the friends go home for the night, the remaining one watches TV, dances, and takes apart his face in front of a giant mirror.

Originally a play, Sorcerer is a book about the pleasures of being together and being alone. The characters find contentment in each other's company, conversing in the placid, eerie rhythms of a sitcom in which conflict never arises. Unease is exported to furniture, gadgets, and bodily movements. The result is a counterintuitive kind of realism, lying somewhere between the procedural and the miraculous. There's levitation.

'Atkins and Zultanski's play redesigns the contemporary home as a machine for comedy, sadness and anxiety. Sorcerer is a unique work of theatre and literature, beautiful and unsettling.' ‚Äì Dan Fox

‚Äî‚Äî

The film version of Sorcerer will be screening as part of my show @gladstone.gallery in New York, which opens Friday, November 17 (more details on that soon), and copies of the book will be available to purchase there.

We'll launch the book in London on Thursday, November 30, at the LRB Bookshop @lrbbookshop Steve and I will be reading from the book and in conversation with Emily LaBarge. Links to buy the book and tickets for the London launch are in my bio.

The book is designed by @joehalesstudio

New Delhi: The Supreme Court‚Äôs three-judge bench, comprising Chief Justice of India D.Y. Chandrachud and Justices J.B. Pardiwala and Manoj Misra, on Tuesday (October 10) directed the listing of the batch of petitions challenging the validity of the electoral bonds scheme for October 31.

The bench held a preliminary hearing in order to familiarise itself with the issues in the case.

The lead petition, filed by the Association of Democratic Reforms (ADR), challenges the Finance Act, 2017 which was enacted as a money bill and introduced the electoral bond scheme for the purpose of electoral funding. The Act also removed the previous limit of 7.5% of the company‚Äôs average three-year net profit for political donations.

As per the scheme, a company is not required to name the political parties to which such contributions are made. The donors‚Äô names are also not revealed to the public.

The petitioners argue that these amendments will result in opaqueness, heighten the odds of conflict of interest and also drastically increase black money and corruption.  The petitioners also claim that this will lead to the creation of shell companies and rise of benami transactions to channelise undocumented money into the political and electoral process in India.

On Tuesday, counsel Prashant Bhushan for the petitioners alleged that due to non-decision on the matter by the court continuously since 2017, the ruling party has been enjoying the fruits of the scheme in every general election to the Lok Sabha as well as the assembly elections, thus upsetting the level playing field.

Read the full story at thewire.in

We love Israel. We hate what is happening there today.

Our hearts are grieving for Israelis and Palestinians who want no part of this war. We are saddened for families torn apart from murder, kidnapping, and their homes destroyed. We know there are parents on both sides right now, who wonder if a rocket will drop out of the sky and destroy their home, or a stray bullet will hit one of their children.

We have deep anger at terrorists who have murdered and raped and terrorized innocent people. We hate that this conflict began with murders of innocent Israelis. We hate the weaponization of religion that leads extremists to justify their violence. We want immediate revenge and justice for those terrorists who have started something that will likely never be unraveled, and will never be forgotten.

And along with all of these thoughts, we are wrestling with understanding how all of this works in an unfolding storyline of history and future. We are working to believe that God will somehow be able to redeem this for the good of people and for His good plans.

We care. But we are also aware that we are powerless to affect anything of consequence. So we‚Äôre thinking. And talking. And we are praying passionately.

We are praying for Israel, for:
|  The violence to end quickly.
|  The terrorists to be captured and justice delivered.
|  Innocent Israelis and Palestinians and other civilians, to be kept out of harms way.
|  That this would not escalate into further significant war.
|  That governments and leaders would value human life enough to sit at a table and at least come to agreements that innocent people cannot be devalued as pawns of war.

The World Food Programme said Tuesday it had partially resumed distributing food aid in Ethiopia, after halting assistance over the diversion of supplies.

The UN agency said the aid was intended only for the country's almost 900,000 refugees living in camps.
The WFP and US agency USAID halted food aid to Africa's second most populous country in June after discovering supplies were not reaching those in need, raising fears millions of Ethiopians would be left in desperate straits.

Around 17% of the country's 120 million people depend on food aid.
Last week USAID said it had resumed food aid to refugees in around 30 camps.

Most refugees in Ethiopia are from Somalia, Eritrea, and South Sudan. Around 35,000 have fled the conflict in neighbouring Sudan in recent months.
"Families living in refugee camps across five regions, including new arrivals who have fled from Sudan, are receiving food parcels for the first time since WFP paused food distributions in June," the WFP said.

"Refugee food security has deteriorated in the past months, leading to increased malnutrition, heightened tensions around the camps and even unsafe journeys back across the border," WFP said.

"Food is a lifeline for refugees living in unimaginably hard conditions, and it's a relief that we now have measures in place to resume vital support," said WFP assistant executive director Valerie Guarnieri.

Write a I realized probably haven't posted my Pattern 14 rifle before.  This one is a bit rough, but solid.  However, unlike the vast majority that I have encountered, this one retained the volley sights.  I'm a bit suspect that the front sight is a replacement, but at least they are still present.

The Pattern 14 is a .303 chambered 5 round magazine capacity rifle that was based on the Pattern 13 rifle that was intended to replace the SMLE.  The Pattern 13 was chambered in .276 Enfield and was based on a modified Mauser action.  This rifle would have been quite a departure from the Lee-Enfield line of rifles then in service in the UK for several decades. 

The outbreak of war in Europe in 1914 interrupted the plan to replace the SMLE.  Therefore, the Pattern 13 concept was abandoned.  All was not lost, however, as the need for as many arms as possible for the conflict led to the UK modifying the Pattern 13 to chamber the in service .303 round and contracting with manufactureres in the the US.  These manufacturers were Remington, Eddystone, and Winchester.

The contracting of the Pattern 14 to US makers allowed British manufacturers to focus on SMLE production for front line soldiers.  The Pattern 14 would be relegated for the most part to second line and reserve troops.  It did, however, stand out in the combat role as a sniper rifle designated the Pattern 14 MKI W (T)....

Found me a swashbuckling pirate! Or is he a privateer? Or a corsair? Or a buccaneer? Are they all the same thing? 

Turns out that no, they are not. 

The most commonly used phrase, pirate, represents a seaman that conducts all sorts of nautical crimes & misbehaviors, like raising ships, robbery, kidnapping, & murd3r. The biggest requirement is that it involves water & a boat (according to Britannica). Some of the most famous pirates include Blackbeard & Captain Kidd, or fictional ones like Captains Hook & Jack Sparrow. 

Piracy is mostly associated with the 17th-18th centuries, known as the Golden Age of Piracy, but pirate attacks are still frequent in waters surrounding Somalia, Indonesia, Nigeria, India, Peru, & Singapore. 

While pirate is the most general term, the others refer to more specific groups. Privateers were pirates with papers, commissioned by governments to attack rivals. They would sail their own privately armed ships & rob & pillage settlements & ships belonging to enemy nations. Francis Drake, for example, was a privateer commissioned by Elizabeth I to plunder Spanish settlements. Of course, privateers didn‚Äôt always follow the rules exactly. 

Corsairs were pirates in the Mediterranean, similar to privateers but with more of a religious tone as they waged conflict between the Islamic Ottoman Empire & Christian states of Europe. The Barbary corsairs notably aligned with the Ottoman Empire but grew beyond their control, while the Knights of St. John in Malta intercepted Muslim ships in the 15-1600s. 

Buccaneers were specific to the Caribbean, beginning with French wild game hunters who committed piracy & based themselves on the island of Tortuga. They attracted other cultures & primarily fought the Spanish. Buccaneers are generally some of the biggest influences to our modern day pop culture view of piracy. 

So - all buccaneers, corsairs, & privateers are pirates - but not all pirates are buccaneers, corsairs, or privateers. Hope that helps clear things up!

VENUS IN VIRGO 9th October - 8th November // ‚ú® Venus now moves into the more pragmatic and orderly sign of Virgo after being in the fun sign of Leo. 
With Venus in this more reserved and modest sign, there will be an energy shift in our love lives that focus on showing love more practically.
Virgo is known for being reliable, loyal and dedicated but it is also know for being a perfectionist and very critical. This can create tension in our relationships as good intentions of trying to help and give advice may be taken as being overly critical and nitpicking our partner. Therefore this is a time to avoid giving unsolicited advice as it is likely to be misunderstood. Be wary of creating unnecessary conflict at this time that may get blown out of proportion. This is also a time where you may have arguments around finances.
Venus represents how we love and what we value, so now is a good time to take note of the things your loved one finds important and to show love in their love language. 
Venus is less powerful in Virgo as it can be a critical, judgemental and a demanding energy. Love does not do well under criticism. Virgos are perfectionist and this energy may make us fixated on trying to have the ‚Äúperfect‚Äù relationship. We may be more inclined to focus on all the things that are wrong instead of being grateful for what is right. By mindful of the ‚Äúnaggy‚Äù critical energy as well as trying to control your partner. Remember that no relationship is perfect and is always a work in progress. Use this time instead to gain more clarity in how to relate to our partners. 
Be mindful also of how you show love to yourself. During this transit we may have very high standards and expectations of ourselves as well as others. Reflect on if being so hard on yourself is fair and conducive to your wellbeing. 
Use this practical Virgo energy to do practical things for your partner like unpacking the dishwasher, rather than shower them with lavish gifts. Venus in Virgo requires love relationships and beauty to be purposeful. Less important is the grand gestures and showy romantic displays of affection.

In San Francisco, hundreds gathered outside the Israeli consulate in Montgomery Street on 10/8 in support of the Palestinian people and to demand an end to the United States‚Äô military aid to the Israeli government. Protesters held up signs and waved Palestinian flags. Nearby, a group supporting Israel also waved flags and held signs. At one point, a scuffle erupted between the two groups.

‚ÄúIt is 2 million people living in prison, what we want is for those 2 million people to be free in Gaza, we want all Palestinians to be able to live on their ancestral lands,‚Äù said Waseem Hajj with the Arab Resource and Organizing Center based in San Francisco, one of the groups that organized the Sunday rally. Hajj stressed that there is a complex history behind the recent violence.

‚ÄúWhen people are caged, they want to be free. You cannot trap 2 million people in ‚Ä¶ the world‚Äôs largest open-air prison and not expect them to fight tooth and nail for their freedom,‚Äù said Hajj. ‚ÄúYou can‚Äôt expect people to roll over and die. You can‚Äôt expect Palestinians to do that. And so I think what I would ask is "why have we allowed the situation?‚Äù

Gabriel Yankulin of San Francisco attended the service at Congregation Sherith Israel. How does lying create psychological dysfunction?

Well, from what I can tell, humans are designed to be truthful. 

On a very basic level, whenever you tell a lie you create a psychological conflict.

Part of you knows and wants to tell the truth, it wants your system clean and clear without any obstructions.

But when you lie, you have to push that part of you out of the way in order to make room for whatever lie you want to tell. 

So right there you‚Äôre already fighting with yourself and you have to divert portion of your mental energy to keeping the truth at bay. 

And depending on the size of the lie, it can take quite a bit of mental energy to keep it down. 

It makes you weaker. 

On top of that, nobody lies being kind to themselves. 

They lie to themselves by forcefully pushing the truth out of the way. 

Sometimes with intense force and personal prejudice. 

So you‚Äôre clogging your system while adding an oppressive ethos to your internal world. 

And that not even to mention the fear of getting caught, having to divert even more mental energy to keeping the lies going and the rotting sense of shame that gets worse over time. 

Knowing yourself to be a fraud. 

But you‚Äôll also eventually project all that force, shame and disdain you feel at the truth on the people you need to hide it from. 

Which not only makes you highly fucking suspicious, but also terrible to be around. 

Yet when you tell the truth‚Ä¶ you‚Äôre unburdened. 

Nothing to fight or keep in order, no shame or paranoia, no clogged up energy slowing you down. 

No bullshit getting in the way between you and those you love. 

Just the ease and peace that comes from accepting what is, as it is. 

There are extreme circumstances where a lie can save your life. 

But for everything else, it hardly seems worth it.

47  Life Lessons üéÇ
. 
Each year,  on my birthday, I love to share life lessons that I've learned and continue to learn throughout the years.
Which life lesson resonates with you?
.
.
1. Set boundaries and, most importantly, adhere to them. The things we complain about the most are indicators of needing healthier boundaries.
 
2. People show peacock feathers when first meeting them. Pay attention to who they are, their consistency, and how they show up after the peacock feathers have disappeared.

3. Pay attention to actions, not words.

4. Accountability is important.

5. Quality over quantity.

6. There are Always 3 sides to every story. Your side, their side, and the truth. Be mindful of the side you take without listening to everyone's side.

7. You only have so many f**ks to give within a lifetime. Stay mindful of who and what you give those to.

8. Support is extremely important. Stay mindful of who supports you during hard times and happy times.

9.Relationships can fade. Good times and trying times from the relationship are both learning experiences and valuable to growth.

10. Healthy relationships can not exist without reciprocity.

11. Money comes and goes, your name, your character, and how you treat others last a lifetime. 

12. You deserve to be heard and seen.
